text: Out with the old in with the new When you ve finished one chapter and before another begins it s time to reflect and remember what makes you really happy Today I ve made a weird discovery about myself I always thought I m more of a hippie person And my favorite travel destinations are all about nature But today I realized that the only place I really really want to go back is NEW YORK I feel trapped Like falling in love with the wrong guy Yes we had amazing time together but it was supposed to be just a holiday romance Now I realized that all this time I was trying to forget you with others my type places And you are too popular too everything Which I don t like usually Yet here I am Giving up and admitting I NY But I won t be thinking about you anymore Have a great life NY nyc love MoMA

text: Photobookview Helen Levitt Slide Show Powerhouse Books New York City s visual poet laureate Helen Levitt renowned for her iconic black and white street photographs also possessed a little known archive of color work which was collected for the first time in Slide Show which was her third PowerHouse Books monograph In and again in Helen Levitt received grants from the Guggenheim Foundation to photograph in color on the streets of New York where she had photographed two decades earlier in black and white But tragically the best of these pioneering color pictures were stolen from her apartment in and she had to start over again In the new work color photos were shown as a continuous slide projection at New York s Museum of Modern Art an early example of a slide show presentation by a museum and one of the first exhibitions of serious color photography anywhere in the world Slide Show presents more than one hundred photographs including eight surviving images from the series more than half of which had never been exhibited or published before Helen Levitt August March was an American photographer She was particularly noted for street photography around New York City and has been called the most celebrated and least known photographer of her time Slide Show Published by PowerBooks Photographs by Helen Levitt Text by John Szarkowski Hardcover x inches pages four color photographs ISBN Images The Helen Levitt Estate Image Slide Show Photobook Cover Sources Powerhousebooks comAmericansuburbx comLensculture con Helenlevitt photobook photobooks slideshow filmphotography documentaryphotography streetphotographynyc colorfilmphotography colorphotography moma newyorkcity nyc filmisnotdead flimisalive analogphoto analogphotography streetphotography mipphotobites mipphotobookview

name: 2019-09-20 01.43.41 2136506315354450276_moma.jpg
text: The Goldfinch dir John Crowley Remember when I said Hustlers had no business being as good as it is well The Goldfinch has no business being this bad What can only be described as the biggest disappointment of the year might prove to be detrimental for many of the people involved in this project Crowley is not looking good even though Brooklyn was nominated for Best Picture just a few years ago Ansel Elgort may have just proved he s not a marketable star Nicole Kidman was flat Finn Wolfhard was hard to watch That s just the performances The story is so convoluted and confused with what it wants to be it completely loses any of the possible emotional appeal it s trying to work towards I understand the book it s based on is very long but that s no excuse for scenes where characters show up once and then disappear for the whole movie At multiple times in this film it almost comes together but it just never seems to There are two quite good things amongst the jumbled mess The first is Roger Deakins cinematography it s gorgeous as usual The second is Jeffrey Wright s performance Whenever he is on screen it s almost as though the film makes sense but as soon as he leaves it s back to its convolution Overall I don t recommend this movie it s too long too confusing and just too much

text: Rembrandt Self Portrait Oil on Canvas Wallraf Richartz Museum wallrafrichartzmuseum The painter has portrayed himself as visibly aged in this work which came at the end of a long series of some self portraits And like no other Rembrandt used them as a means of psychological research into his self Thus his gaze which is currently directed to the viewer was primarily directed to his reflection His raised eyebrows and open perhaps laughing mouth tell of the way he flouted every convention with a buoyancy that only advanced age allows And so Rembrandt documented his own physiognomy with a ruthless directness and with so much paint we almost literally feel the furrows on his brow and cheeks and the heavy bags under his eyes But what might have prompted Rembrandt to laugh This question has occupied art historians for decades because the painting does not give any clues that allow a definite answer Is the just vaguely distinguishable figure on the left hand margin a sculpture or is it a painted image on an easel Is Rembrandt showing himself here as a painter with brush and maulstick A variety of interpretations have been found for this painting some have concluded that the god Terminus is standing before Rembrandt reminding him of his approaching end Others have seen this figure as the weeping Heraclitus so that Rembrandt as a champion of a cheerful approach to life is portraying himself in the contrasting role of the laughing philosopher Democritus And finally some have tried to see it as the antique painter colleague Zeuxis who allegedly laughed himself to death at the sight of a ludicrous wizened old woman Via wallrafrichartzmuseum

text: Kenneth Nolan Pink Lady Kenneth Noland s Color Field painting which was categorized by Clement Greenberg as belonging to the Post Painterly Abstraction movement was some of the most focused and consistent art produced in mid th century America After studying under such artists as Ilya Bolotowsky and Josef Albers and working alongside fellow second generation Color Field abstractionists like Helen Frankenthaler and Morris Louis Noland developed a signature style based on simplified abstract forms including targets chevrons and stripes Noland s paintings are characterized by strikingly minimalist compositions of shape and color In this regard Noland s art has influenced a wide range of contemporary abstractionists who continue to experiment with highly simplified forms and pure saturated color Via theartstory org

text: Abapuru de Tarsila do Amaral Infelizmente muitos brasileiros ainda menosprezam a arte produzida em nosso pa s Em contrapartida milhares de turistas se aglomeraram no Museu de Arte Moderna de Nova York MOMA para apreciar uma exposi o dedicada exclusivamente para Tarsila Abaporu uma cl ssica pintura do modernismo brasileiro Considerada a obra prima da autora a tela foi pintada a leo em para ser oferecida ao seu ent o marido o escritor Oswald de Andrade O nome da obra de origem tupi guarani e significa homem que come gente canibal ou antrop fago Enquanto os membros agigantados representam o trabalho bra al do povo brasileiro a cabe a menor pode indicar uma suposta falta de pensamento cr tico e apaziguamento da popula o Por conta desses elementos tal pintura vista como uma cr tica social Em a tela foi vendida para o colecionador argentino Eduardo Costantini em um leil o pelo valor de milh o de reais arteexplicada brasil tarsila tarsiladoamaral moma genius pintores artemoderna museum art museu artistasfamosos

text: ROTHKO THE FRIENDLY GHOST GLOW IN THE DARK RENDITION x CANVAS ANOTHER CONTEMPORARY CONCEPT FROM son of a finch When I was a younger man art was a lonely thing No galleries no collectors no critics no money Yet It was golden age for we all had nothing to lose and a vision to gain Today it is not quite the same It is a time of tons of verbiage activity consumption Which condition is better for the world at large I will not venture to discuss But I do know that many of those that are driven to this life are desperately searching for those pockets of silence Where we can root and grow We must all hope we find them Mark Rothko contemporaryart popart abstractart abstractexpressionism modernart gallery gallerywall abstractpainting abstractexpressionist finchoriginal markrothko art artist artistsoninstagram artistofinstagram moma met metmuseum markrothkoart gagosian aninaarts therealswizzz complexart highmuseumofart

text: Repost From robertdenirosr save repost On October th join Robert De Niro at the nd Street Y as he discusses the life and career of his father Robert De Niro Sr with art historian Robert Storr Robert Storr is an artist curator and critic based in New York and New Haven Formerly the Senior Curator of Painting and Sculpture at the Museum of Modern Art in New York he was the first Rosalie Solow Professor of Modern Art at the Institute of Fine Arts New York University and subsequently the Dean of the Yale School of Art in New Haven He was also the first American Director of Visual Arts of the Venice Biennale In the late s he briefly served as co Dean of the New York Studio School of Painting and Sculpture where he met Robert De Niro Sr on several occasions He is also a contributing writer to the upcoming monograph Robert De Niro Sr Paintings Drawings and Writings Click the link in our bio to purchase tickets ndstreety rizzolibooks dcmooregallery meganfoxkelly sed robertdenirosr robertdeniro artist art painting drawing writing poetry portrait stilllife nudes interiors oeuvre rizzoli monograph y robstorr robertstorr arthistorian legacy fatherandson moma metmuseum

text: Winter Landscape c Painted by Ivan Aivazovsky Born July Feodosia Crimea Ukraine Died May Feodosia Crimea Ukraine Oil on canvas x cm Famous Armenian painter who knew the sea and loved it sincerely Drawing ability of young Aivazovsky attracted the attention of A Kaznacheyev the town governor who helped Aivazovsky to enter the high school at Simferopol and in the St Petersburg Academy of Arts At the age of twenty he graduated from the Art Academy of St Petersburg with a gold medal At the age of he have already gained international fame During the period of Aivazovsky as a pensioner of the Academy of Arts spent time in Italy traveled to Germany France Spain and Holland He worked much and had many exhibitions meeting everywhere with success He painted a lot of marine landscapes which became very popular in Italy Aivazovsky s name is intricately bound with the sea Perhaps no one in Europe has painted the extraordinary beauty of the sea with so much feeling and expressiveness as Aivazovsky has writes V Adasov When in the artist returned to St Petersburg he was awarded the title of Academician and became attached to the General Naval Headquarters This allowed him to travel much with Russian fleet expeditions on different missions he visited Turkey Greece Egypt America From to he painted several canvases with naval warfare as the subject the pictures portrayed historical battles of the Russian Fleet Neither financial security nor life in Palace interested him He returned to his native land built a workplace home on the seashore and until the last days of his life dedicates himself to the work that he loved Aivazovsky left more than pictures Most of his works are world famous Fig Details

text: The Starry Night is an oil on canvas by the Dutch post impressionist painter Vincent van Gogh Painted in June it describes the view from the east facing window of his asylum room at Saint R my de Provence just before sunrise with the addition of an ideal village It has been in the permanent collection of the Museum of Modern Art in New York City since acquired through the Lillie P Bliss Bequest Regarded as among Van Gogh s finest works The Starry Night is one of the most recognized paintings in the history of Western culture moma vangogh love art book museum magazine artlovers homotempus nyc exhibition vincentvangogh

text: hitchcock Drama is life with the dull bits cut out I never said all actors are cattle what I said was all actors should be treated like cattle Always make the audience suffer as much as possible There is no terror in the bang only in the anticipation of it Blondes make the best victims They re like virgin snow that shows up the bloody footprints For me the cinema is not a slice of life but a piece of cake The length of a film should be directly related to the endurance of the human bladder Give them pleasure the same pleasure they have when they wake up from a nightmare If it s a good movie the sound could go off and the audience would still have a perfectly clear idea of what was going on The only way to get rid of my fears is to make films about them

text: V E L E S life triumphs over death sw n One of the most difficult design tasks is that of the monument because it belongs to the domain of non programmatic architecture The monument is a fixation of certain act for future generations But this fixation doesn t mean oblivion That s why the monument must be introduced into the cycle of life I am not for a monument that is experienced in one moment of intense emotions in pain in suffering but rather for a continued experience for the liberation of the sanctity and dignity for the feeling that life triumphs over death painting art digitalart artwork drawing artstation artoftheday fantasy digitalpainting design epicart fantasyepic epic conceptart deviantart artstagram pinterest fantasyart photoshop design wallpaper architecture people moma monument landscape fantasylandscape fantasyartwork castle illustrate it illustrarch letsshowitbetter anti reality arch impressive archistic use photoshop hustler archisketcher parametric architecture architrendz archdaily dezeen arch viz

text: Giorgio de Chirico The Soothsayer s Recompense Oil on Canvas On ViewPhiladelphia Museum of Art philamuseum This painting is one of a series of melancholic cityscapes that de Chirico painted featuring a lone statue in a deserted Italian piazza The antique statue represents the sleeping Ariadne who according to Greek mythology was abandoned by her lover on the desert island of Naxos The confrontation of the classical world with a modern steam engine in the distance creates an uneasy ambiguity of time and space Via philamuseum

text: PSC s Bachelor of Photography graduate Sarah Walker is launching her new photobook Pel i Manor at the New York Art Book Fair at MoMA The Museum of Modern Art this weekend Published by Australian publishers Perimeter Books Sarah s work was shot over three days in the attic of Pel i Manor a grand th century art nouveau structure in the small Latvian town of Kuld ga She offers an ominous curious and claustrophobic vantage on this historically loaded building The site where Latvia ceded independence to Nazi occupation during World War II today the building is used as a school for disabled children Congratulations Sarah we are so proud of you Learn more about the book and order your copy from perimeterbooks sarahjwalker printedmatter artbookfairs printedmatterinc themuseumofmodernart beinspired beglobal beconnnected photobookfair nyabf nyabf printedmatter newyork bookfair photobook photobookarchive moma photographer photographers Australianphotographer pscmelb learnphotography photographycollege university photographycourse bachelorofphotography photographydegree bachlorofarts pelcimanor latvia

text: Be free e un progetto artistico sviluppato nel definito Performance Photography Desideravo rompere il mio legame con la fotografia accademica per iniziare un nuovo processo di creazione L idea consisteva nel coinvolgere persone conosciute e sconosciute di tutta Europa e dar a loro la possibilita di intervenire materialmente sulla mia mia immagine Ricordo di aver selezionato la carta su cui stampare il mio ritratto stampe selezionato oltre indirizzi di sconosciuti in giro per l Europa preparato un foglio bianco dove poter scrivere un pensiero due buste francobolli etc Dopo un mese ero estasiato avevo ricevuto immagini via posta o tramite intermediari Ogni immagine raccontava una storia una emozione un pensiero Aver completato questo progetto mi ha dato la possibilita di abbandonare la mia zona di confort e di sperimentare con nuove forme e materiali Be free ha ricevuto una Menzione d onore a Moscow International Foto Award e selezionato da da una associazione artistica Photo soup per la pubblicazione in formato cartacea di un libro arts arte artoftheday art moma contemporaryart art arte artsy artist artwork artistic nuuco artist conceptualart performingartsphotography artecontemporaneaitaliana

name: 2019-09-21 17.14.38 2137699652764585994_moma.jpg
text: The Edge of the Woods c Painted by Charles Courtney Curran Born February Hartford United States Died November New York United States An Impressionist figure genre and landscape painter Charles Curran is known as a prolific artist who created light filled paintings often of young women Curran was born in Hartford Kentucky but in moved to Sandusky Ohio After studying one year at the Cincinnati School of Design he began a distinguished career when he moved to New York City in and enrolled in the National Academy of Design There he studied under Walter Satterlee At age he had his first public exhibition at the Academy and won numerous prizes from that time onward Five years later he received the Academy s Third Hallgarten Prize for A Breezy Day which was considered the most meritorious painting in oil Following his training at the National Academy he became a student at the Art Students League He then studied at the Academie Julian in Paris from to The French artist Jules Bastien Lepage was a source of inspiration for Curran with his paintings of peasants as a common subject matter From to he exhibited regularly at the Pennsylvania Academy In artist Frederick Dellenbaugh invited Curran to Cragsmoor an art center in the Hudson River Valley near Ellenville New York In Curran moved into a house there and established a studio At this time he turned to the themes and Impressionist style that would occupy most of the remaining years of his life young women in bright sunlight His female subjects are often elegantly dressed posed and feminine with uncomplicated and dreamy gazes Curran later included flowered backgrounds in his paintings a theme to last the remainder of his career He occasionally painted portraits and landscapes as well as a series of views of the Imperial Temples of Peking His works can be seen in collections at the Columbus Museum of Art in Ohio the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City the National Gallery of Art in Washington D C and the Toledo Museum of Art in Ohio Fig Details

text: Moschino Spring ready to wear pt Jeremy Scott has surpassed himself in this collection He decided to be inspired by Pablo Picasso and his muses being a very creative person he transformed his models into real artists Bella Hadid played the harlequin while Kaia Gerber was the girl with the mandolin Jeremy wanted to show off his most creative talent and his talent in concretizing fantasies The idea was clear the model is like a canvas in fact Ciara Taylor herself wore a dress in the shape of a giant framed canvas with a female nude on it Scott said in the backstage that all the prints were hand painted in the studio before being digitized The Moschino fashion shows always have a great social impact paper dolls have been the removal of our popular social media culture while The Price Is Right was about hyperconsumerism On this occasion Jeremy wanting to be inspired by Picasso probably wanted to hit the theme of MASTERY fashion fashionshow fashionweek beautiful picasso art met moma newyork manhattan paris london milano moschino jeremyscott instagram insta instafashion like follow

text: Inspiration comes this week from Swedish designer Bruno Mathsson The son of a cabinet maker he drew on tradition even as he devised new bentwood techniques for his signature chairs and shelves seen here He also pioneered the use of hemp webbing for chairs and other upholstery and was the first in Sweden to use heated floors in his glass houses with purpose built double and triple pane windows We love the warm natural wood and simple lines that perfectly balance coziness and functionality at the Bruno Mathsson Center He was also a favorite of MoMA s first Industrial Design Director Edgar Kaufman Jr who had one of his chairs in his famous Frank Lloyd Wright home Fallingwater mathsson naturalwood bentwood furnituredesign bentwoodfurniture hemp hempfurniture sweden swedishdesign swedishdesigner swedisharchitecture swedisharchitect pendantlamp officedesign customshelving modularshelving modularfurniture midcenturydesign moma fallingwater franklloydwright chairdesign industrialdesign midcentury interiors interiordesign heatedfloors bookshelf desk

text: Happy Birthday to Italian satirical artist MaurizioCattelan Born on this day in Artwork Frank and Jamie Polyester resin wax pigment human hair clothing shoes and accessories Frank x x Jaime x x Limited edition of plus artist s proof This sculpture work sold at Phillips New York November th for Lot No Maurizio Cattelan was born in Padua Italy in Cattelan who has no formal training and considers himself an art worker rather than an artist has often been characterized as the court jester of the art world This label speaks not only to his taste for irreverence and the absurd but also his profound interrogation of socially ingrained norms and hierarchies subjects historically only available to the court fool christies sothebys phillips popartist popart andywarhol warhol duanehanson stdibs contemporarypainting nycart moma museumofmodernart modernart contemporaryart gravesinternationalart artmuseum italianartist damienhirst hirst banksy jeffkoons cattelan guggenheimmuseum guggenheim sculptureart sculptor hyperrealism hyperrealistic

text: Mimmo Rotella Circo Orfei screenprint in colours with torn poster collage cm x Italian master Rotella was one of the most iconic creative minds during the postwar period Known worldwide for his d collage he was a member of the Nouveau R alisme an artistic movement founded in by the art critic Pierre Restany and the renowned painter Yves Klein During the s Rotella started to exhibit his d collage and retro posters It was the start of a revolutionary artistic approach that paved the way for his international success Rotella s artworks are now exhibited in the most important cultural institutions of the world like the National Gallery of Art Washington D C the Centre Georges Pompidou Paris the Tate Modern London The Museum of Modern Art MOMA New York and the Peggy Guggenheim Collection Venice

text: LC Basculant Chairs by Le Corbusier Charlotte Perriand and Pierre Jeanneret Cassina circa Stunning pair of original LC Basculant armchairs by Le Corbusier Pierre Jeanneret Charlotte Perriand Italy circa on chrome tubular frames with adjustable back rests upholstered cream canvas with tan leather strap arm rests each stamped to underside LC LC These lightweight and compact chairs are a counterpoint to the LC chair a true classic design of th century Charles Edouard Jeanneret known as Le Corbusier was born at La Chaux de Fonds in Switzerland in he died in France in The multi talented Le Corbusier was at the same time a painter architect designer and writer he is now recognised as one of the most influential architects of th century design These beauties have now been fully restored to perfection by our close friends at Rhubarb Dimensions Width inch cmDepth inch cmHeight inch cmSeat H inch cm We love Le Corbusier cassina lecorbusier lc moma knoll basculant midcenturydesign charlesedouardjeanneret midcenturymoderndesign midcenturymodern interiordesigner rhubarbchairs interiordesigners charlotteperriand pierrejeanneret interiorstylist chairs splendidantiques stdibs newyork london paris losangeles la ny hk dubai

text: BEING A MOTHER IS EXHAUSTING I realised only After i became one But Exhaustion does not come from the child Not from the physical activities of the child Not from the caretaking activities of the child Exhausting is mental and emotional Its from the feeling that you are not a good enough Mother and you are not a good enough Wife Exhausting is come from constant nagging and criticism that comes your way from the day you give birth to your little one That the child head is not Round Enough Exhausting comes from the Undue and Unwanted opinions from Relatives It comes from comparision that your baby does not have enough weight That your baby does not walk yet That your baby does not have teeth yet or your baby does not eat enough If something went wrong with the child it is because mother did not take care The mother did not do what she should have Remember one thing today if you can t leave your own life behind your needs and your dreams for that child if you can t wash the poop and pees five times a day or wake up every two hours to feed a child YOU HAVE NO RIGHT TO CRITICIZE THE MOTHER The last thing she needs a another person makind her feel that she isn t doing enough Show a little compassion Keep your words to yourself Keep your taunts and negativity to your self SHOW A LITTLE LOVE TO EVERY MOTHER OUT THERE AND SHARE IF YOU AGREE bloggerstylefashion writeup motherhood mommylifeisthebestlife moma islamabadian islamabadstreetfashion islamabadgram pakistan pakistaniinfluencer palm mydubai dubaifoodies dubaiblog hijab hijabstyle lookbook hijabinspiration abaya hijabtrend hijabinspiration ajmanclub ajmanguide sharjaha trendingpost trendingtoday

text: Just got back from a trip to Keble College Oxford where my uncle Vitit Muntarbhorn KBE was selected to be part of an exhibition Portrait of Keble which marks the beginning of the th anniversary of the college In Vitit Muntarbhorn was selected as the first UN Expert to protect LGBTQ against violence and discrimination setting a clear mandate to decriminalise same sex relations globally And with his previous positions as the UN Special Rapporteur on Human Rights in North Korea and as a member of UN Commissions of Inquiry covering Syria and the Ivory Coast he was knighted for his contribution to International Human Rights in individuals were selected from years of co education at Keble for their inspirational achievements be they personal professional or both My heart is filled with gratitude to attend this event Dreams really do come true WatchTheMuntarbhorns

text: PRAGMA old Gold TREE OF LOVE Rug series based on real Tree of Life Persian rugs REY UK Follow Amazing Artist reyzorroPragma love in the BiblePragma is a kind of practical love founded on reason or duty and one s longer term interests Sexual attraction takes a back seat in favour of personal qualities and compatibilities shared goals and making it work In the days of arranged marriages pragma must have been very common Tree of life rugs also known as Tree rugs earn distinction as a representation of one of the most timeless religious symbols of human life its use preceding Christianity and Islam Ancient cultures throughout Europe and Asia view the tree of life as a link between man and heaven Often in Oriental rug producing areas Tree of Life rugs are produced as prayer rugs In Islam the Tree of Life remains an important metaphor for the pathway between Heaven Earth and the underworld of Hell contemporaryart reyzorro whitecubegallery artnyc moma whitecube whitechapelgallery gagosian themet liquidskydsign saatchigallery miamibasel serpentineuk tatemodernmuseum tatemodern tatemodernlondon haywardgallery barbicancentre pacegallery artsy londonartwalk thefallmag artmazemag biennial museumofmodernart tatebritainmuseum damienhirst NewMediaArt artbasel

text: Gustav Klimt Hope II Oil gold and platinum on canvas x cm Museum of Modern Art New York Austrian painter Gustav Klimt was Vienna s most renowned advocator of Art Nouveau or as the style was known in Germany Jugendstil Initially successful as a conventional academic painter he developed his own eclectic decorative and often erotic style His position as the co founder and first president of the Vienna Secession ensured that this style would become widely influential Klimt s style is highly ornamental He favored organic lines and used a lot of gold and silver colors in his art work certainly an heritage from his father s profession as a gold and silver engraver His sumptuous ornate paintings in which the figures are nearly submerged in a mosaic of jewel like color and gold were a scandal at his time because of the display of nudity and the subtle sexuality and eroticism Klimt s famous work Hope II refers to the German expression in guter hoffnung in good hope which refers to a woman being pregnant The elongated and bare breasted female figure is indeed pregnant which is are rare subject in art history Klimt painted Hope I in Because he depicted the pregnant woman naked it was rejected by the censors for an exhibition in the Secession building on the grounds of obscenity In Hope II he dressed the female figure in a sumptuous gown or cloak The composition is full of symbolic imagery One of the most interesting aspects of the work are the three women with bowed heads at the woman s feet With their eyes closed they solemnly raise their hands And then there is the mysterious skull that pops up from her heavily decorated gown or cloak Skulls are a frequently used vanitas symbol in art history a constant reminder of death and the transience of life Check out my other accounts art questions and debates my favorite work of art gustavklimt klimt historyofart arthistory historiadelarte secession storiadellarte artnouveau jugendstil modernart symbolism text: Ni o Comiendo Sand a c Painted by Joaqu n Sorolla y Bastida Born February Valencia Spain Died August Cercedilla Spain Oil on canvas x cm Cuando apenas contaba dos a os de edad fallecieron sus padres v ctimas de una epidemia de c lera Al quedar hu rfanos fueron acogidos su hermana Eugenia y l por su t a Isabel hermana de su madre y su marido de profesi n cerrajero Pasados los a os su t o intent ense arle en vano el oficio de la cerrajer a advirtiendo pronto que su verdadera vocaci n era la pintura Un viaje a Par s en lo puso en contacto con la pintura impresionista lo que supuso una verdadera revoluci n en su estilo Abandon los temas anteriores y comenz a pintar al aire libre dej ndose invadir por la luz y el color del Mediterr neo Son precisamente las obras de colores claros y pincelada vigorosa que reproducen escenas a orillas del mar las que m s se identifican con el arte de Sorolla Sin embargo fue un artista muy activo que realiz tambi n numerosos retratos de personalidades espa olas y algunas obras de denuncia social bajo la influencia de su amigo Blasco Ib ez Su estilo agradable y f cil hizo que recibiera innumerables encargos que le permitieron gozar de una desahogada posici n social Su fama rebas las fronteras espa olas para extenderse por toda Europa y Estados Unidos donde expuso en varias ocasiones De a pint una serie de murales con temas regionales para la Hispanic Society of America de Nueva York En el estilo m s caracter stico de Sorolla el de t cnica y concepci n impresionista destaca la representaci n de la figura humana ni os desnudos mujeres con vestidos vaporosos sobre un fondo de playa o de paisaje donde los reflejos las sombras las transparencias la intensidad de la luz y el color transfiguran la imagen y dan valor a temas en s mismo intrascendentes Algunos cr ticos consideran estas obras un cruce entre los impresionistas franceses y los acuarelistas ingleses Existe una importante colecci n de pintura suya en el Museo Sorolla de Madrid Fig Details

text: William Glackens Beach with Figures Bellport Oil on Canvas On ViewThe Barnes Foundation barnesfoundation William Glackens invigorated American painting from its Eurocentric tradition bound academicism bringing the observational skills learned as a newspaper illustrator to new urban subjects One of the first American artists to find success without training in Europe Glackens s attention to color and expressive brushwork along with his willingness to experiment marked a turn towards modernism A founding member of the group of artists known as The Eight also referred to by critics and later scholars as the Ashcan School Glackens differed from his colleagues by focusing more on scenes of leisure and entertainment rather than the slums of the Lower East Side He was also unapologetic of his admiration for European painting and popularized the quick brushwork and bright palettes of the Impressionists among American audiences Via theartstory org

text: Kazuo Shiraga No T Oil on canvas L vy Gorvy levygorvy Kazuo Shiraga was born in in Amagasaki Japan After studying Nihon ga Japanese style painting in Kyoto and growing frustrated with the stylistic and material confines he found in Nihon ga Shiraga participated in Gendai Bijutsu Kondankai Contemporary Art Discussion Group with several other students and began experimenting with making oil paintings using his hands and fingers Shiraga found the viscosity of tube ready oil paint more free than the inconvenient and thin ink based pigments he had used in painting school In Shiraga joined renowned Japanese avant garde collective Gutai and was inspired by Gutai s leader Jiro Yoshihara to further push his performative material driven painting practice in order to make something that never existed before During his time as a member of Gutai Shiraga simultaneously pursued oil painting and performance often integrating the two practices in performance painting pieces as Challenging Mud in which the artist used his entire body to manipulate mud as if it were thick pliable paint and Ultramodern Sanbaso in which he wore a dramatic red costume with elongated and wing like arms his movements creating slashes of color against the stark black backdrop of the stage Shiraga continued this exploration of the relationship between body and material over the course of his career and is best known for the large scale foot paintings he made well into his eighties The foot paintings explore themes of Japanese history Chinese mythology and Buddhism while preserving the explosive movements of an artist who continuously sought a dynamic and collaborative relationship with his medium Via levygorvy

text: Il ponte giapponese un dipinto realizzato a olio su tela nel circa dal pittore francese Claude Monet Misura cm x Il soggetto ispirato al giardino in stile giapponese del pittore presso Giverny dove egli coltivava diverse piante esotiche che decoravano un ponticello di legno Lo dipingeva in varie ore del giorno per vedere la luce del sole come cambiava Le pennellate sono veloci intense e in direzioni diverse in modo da dare l impressione del movimento La luce si riflette sulle foglie degli alberi e le ombre diventano colorate Questo dipinto trasmette dei sentimenti forti e contrastanti attraverso il giallo ed il rosso The Japanese bridge Is a painting made in oil on canvas in about by the French painter Claude Monet Measure x cm The subject is inspired by the painter s Japanese style garden near Giverny where he cultivated several exotic plants that decorated a wooden bridge He painted it at various times of the day to see how the sunlight changed The brushstrokes are fast intense and in different directions in order to give the impression of movement The light reflects on the leaves of the trees and the shadows become colored This painting conveys strong and contrasting feelings through yellow and red IlPosteGiapponese TheJapaneseabridge ClaudeMonet Monet French MoMA NewYork USA MuseumofModerArt dipintifamosi dipinto arthistory art social ART undipintoalgiorno arte quadri cultura bellezza MASM MoreArtonSocialMedia follow like instalike instafollow follow me

text: Dark a sutra is the first act of Nasty Temple our project selected for the section An Activism in Design mentored by jerszyseymourdesignworkshop for forecast platform at radialsystem berlin Dark a sutra is a scenography and performance starting from Kar a sutra Mario Bellini s contribution to the polemic exhibition Italy The New Domestic Landscape Part of the performance is the audio of a Bellini s interview in which the architect affirms how the market coopted his car for the future nomad of the Free Love movement thus transforming it in the Multi Purpose Vehicle symbol of the patriarchal family par excellence Dark a sutra has to be seen as a funeral a celebration a sacrifice of the designer as we know it thus accepting the necessity to rethink the designer as a villain an anti hero that can fight the exploitation and cultural appropriation of his practice of resistance This is the act where the designer understands his degenerated nature and sacrifices his ego The darkest desires drive him to a new level of consciousness Thanks to forecast platform radialsystem berlin and all the team for the support Thanks to Jerszy Seymour for the precious support Thanks to questioncollective antoon steenbock peter behrbohm for the exchange and the healthy competitiveness Ph Camille Blake camille blake and Parasite darkasutra karasutra mariobellini thenewdomesticlandscape moma nyk momanyk nasty temple nastytemple parasiteparasite parasite forecast forecatsforum forecastplatform berlin radialsystem performingart theater performance

name: 2019-09-23 20.31.01 2139248043798874006_moma.jpg
text: Two Studies for a Self Portrait Painting It was originally intended to depict a chimpanzee in long grass parts of which may be still visible Bacon then attempted to paint a bird of prey landing in a field In an interview with David Sylvester in Bacon recalls FB Well one of the pictures I did in which was the thing that s in the Museum of Modern Art DS The butcher shop picture FB Yes It came to me as an accident I was attempting to make a bird alighting on a field And it may have been bound up in some way with the three forms that had gone before but suddenly the line that I had drawn suggested something totally different and out of this suggestion arose this picture I had no intention to do this picture I never thought of it in that way It was like one continuous accident mounting on top of another The previous year Poussin s The Adoration of the Golden Calf had been taken into the National Gallery collection and Bacon almost certainly had this painting at the back of his mind in respect of the garlands the calf now slaughtered and the tented Israelite encampment now transmuted into an umbrella Graham Sutherland saw Painting in the Cromwell Place studio and urged his dealer Erica Brausen then of the Redfern gallery to go to see the painting and to buy it Brausen wrote to Bacon several times and visited his studio in early autumn promptly buying the work for Within a fortnight of the sale of Painting to the Hanover gallery Bacon had used the proceeds to decamp from London to Monte Carlo After staying at a succession of hotels and flats including the H tel de R Bacon settled in a large villa La Frontali re in the hills above the town Eric Hall and Nanny Lightfoot would come to stay Bacon spent much of the next few years in Monte Carlo apart from short visits to London From Monte Carlo Bacon wrote to Graham Sutherland and Erica Brausen His letters to Erica Brausen show that he did paint there but no paintings are known to survive francisbacon bacon moma text: Over a vast oeuvre spanning for more than sixty years Bourgeois plumbed the depths of human emotion further and more passionately than perhaps any other artist of her time Evoking the nightmarish and surreal Bourgeois huge spider installation may be viewed in terms of Western arts as the ability to embody both wonder and terror We find in this sculpture the metaphors of spinning weaving care and protection The maternity theme is also present when we look under the abdomen a kind of fenced pocket holds marble eggs thewomanartist louisebourgeois artist artwork artoftheday instagram painting acrylic oil london sculpture curator beirut spain contemporary contemporaryart pastecolors brushstrokes art newyork france paris spider woman wood pigment contemporaryart tate spider museumofmodernart moma ny

name: 2019-09-23 22.53.06 2139319558384110864_moma.jpg
text: Celebrating Russian American artist Louise Nevelson born Leah Berliawsky on this day in in Kiev She explored painting drawing and sculpture but found her niche working with wood a medium from her childhood as her father worked as a woodcutter when the family moved to Maine in the early s An independent woman she divorced her husband of ten years Charles Nevelson a wealthy businessman and endured poverty and rejection to pursue her art She is best known for her monochromatic wall assemblages typically made of found wood objects and her monumental sculptures Most often her pieces are painted black a color that Nevelson saw as all encompassing and regal Sky Cathedral is a massive installation ft x ft x in consisting of some stacked wooden milk crates each containing an assortment of wooded items that Nevelson found on the streets of Manhattan Painting the entire work a single color removes the association and weight of each item and unifies the piece The scope and palette of Nevelson s works were revolutionary for a female artist art russianamericanartist louisenevelson sculpture foundobjectsculpture assemblage assemblageart monochromatic skycathedral onthisday birthdaytoday moma

text: A Young Girl in Profile c Painted by William Adolphe Bouguereau Born November La Rochelle France Died August La Rochelle France aged Oil on canvas x cm His work was characterized by a highly finished technically impeccable realism and a sentimental interpretation of his subject matter Bouguereau received many honours in the s and s and became for a time the most famous French painter of his day In his later years he decorated the chapels of several Parisian churches and painted religious compositions in a Pre Raphaelite style Throughout the course of his life Bouguereau executed known finished paintings although the whereabouts of many are still unknown Fig Details museum moma metmuseum museedulouvre britishmuseum nationalgallery museodelprado vangoghmuseum brooklynmuseum artforum artbasel tatemodern instamuseum rijksmuseum whitneymuseum nationalgalleryofvictoria nationalmuseum gettymuseum curator graffiti streetart oilpainting realism williamadolphebouguereau larochelle france yourarttimes

text: Fernand Leger s Le Petit Dejeuner in the home of Burton and Emily Tremaine This work was which is related to the artist s Le Grand Dejuener in the collection of themuseumofmodernart was sold by from Emily Tremaine s estate at Christie s in to a buyer rumored to be the late shipping magnate Sammy Ofer Most of the Tremaine s collection which ranged from Piet Mondrian to Mark Rothko to Tom Wesselmann was dispersed over a series of auctions It had been promised to the ngadc in Washington which ended up with a few key Kline works and Warhol s A Boy for Meg but when the couple realized how much of the collection would be relegated to storage they rescinded the pledge This detail of a photograph of the apartment is by artist Louise Lawler livingwithart artinthehome fernandleger mondrian markrothko tremainecollection emilytremaine moma museumofmodernart schoolofparis tubism cubism

text: Paula Modersohn Becker Self Portrait with Two Flowersin Her Raised Left Hand Oil on Canvas Not on ViewThe Museum of Modern Art themuseumofmodernart In this emblematic self portrait the pregnant artist stares at viewers with a steady compelling gaze One hand is raised holding two stylized flowers while the other rests over her swelling belly Born in Dresden Modersohn Becker studied in Berlin from to then moved to Worpswede an artists community north of Bremen There she met her husband the artist Otto Modersohn as well as the poet Rainer Maria Rilke who became a close companion Worpswede s artists were known for their commitment to nature and to positive depictions of the local villagers but Modersohn Becker soon grew restless Between and her death in she made four trips to Paris studying ancient sculpture and Egyptian mummy portraits at the Louvre and visiting other museums and galleries all of which profoundly impacted her last great period of work Best known for penetrating self portraits characterized by psychological introspection as well as material and stylistic experimentation Modersohn Becker is also thought to be the first woman to paint female nudes In this artwork painted the year of her death her masklike visage combined with the areas of thick paint on her brow and right eyelid the literal carving of a flower into her cheek likely done with the end of a brush and the vivid expressionistic palette all mark Modersohn Becker as a pioneering contemporary of Henri Matisse and Pablo Picasso Via themuseumofmodernart

text: Henri Matisse Breakfast Oil on Canvas On ViewPhiladelphia Museum of Art philamuseum Most of the paintings that Henri Matisse made in Nice in the s feature female models in richly decorated hotel interiors Breakfast depicts nineteen year old model Antoinette Arnoux in the artist s opulently furnished room at the H tel de la M diterran e Seated with a book on her lap Arnoux has a contemplative self absorbed pose as if lost in thought The color pattern and brushstrokes that animate the room around Arnoux are typical of Matisse s Nice period but the feeling of ennui the sense of intimacy and the emphasis on the psychological state of the model mark a distinct departure from the artist s earlier work Via philamuseum

text: EXPOSICI N EN EL MUSEO DE SAN JUAN DE LA MATAEl de julio de se ha inaugurado una nueva exposici n con el t tulo EL FUEGO EN EL PRADOHomenaje al Museo del Prado en su Bicentenario Complementa y ampl a la exposici n anterior sobre el mismo tema pero con obras pertenecientes al Museo del Prado Vel zquez Rubens Goya El Bosco Cossiers Y como plato fuerte Un cuadro viviente Santalla StrartS y QuinSan han creado la Asociaci n de Museos Virtuales cuyo fin es que todos los pueblos independientemente de su poblaci n puedan disponer de un museo de arte El lema es NING N PUEBLO SIN MUSEO EXHIBITION AT THE SAN JUAN DE LA MATA MUSEUMOn July a new exhibition with the title was inaugurated THE FIRE IN THE PRADOTribute to the Prado Museum in its BicentennialIt complements and extends the previous exhibition on the same subject but with works belonging to the Museo del Prado Vel zquez Rubens Goya El Bosco Cossiers And as a main course A living painting Santalla StrartS and QuinSan have created the Association of Virtual Museums whose goal is that all peoples regardless of their population can have an art museum The motto is NO PEOPLE WITHOUT MUSEUM museodelprado reinasofiamuseum caixaforum museothyssen hermitagemuseum whitneymuseum centrepompidou nationalgallery moma modernart museedorsay louvre met britishmuseum tatemodern guggenheim nycart brooklynmuseum lacmamuseum gemaldegalerie artinstitutechicago ufizzi louvreabudhabi yaleartgallery galleriaborghese gettymuseum sfmoma nationalgalleryofart altepinakothek rijksmuseum

name: 2019-09-24 15.21.03 2139816811636532499_moma.jpg
text: Box Seats at the Theater the Gentleman and the Lady c Painted by Felix Vallotton Born December Lausanne Switzerland Died December Paris France Oil on canvas x cm He was a member the Nabis group who at the end of the th century combined the Post Impressionist techniques and style with new avant garde methods Although he never achieved the same level of prestige as Pierre Bonnard the leader of the Nabis Vallotton is a regular name in art auctions and his works are exhibited in the most reputable museums and galleries In his early years he became interested in portrait painting He occasionally returned to Switzerland where he painted landscapes in the region of Vaud In Paris he became interested in the art of engraving Two of his etchings were inspired by Jean Fran ois Millet and Rembrandt In he produced his first woodcuts and presented ten paintings in his debut at the Salon des Ind pendants Around this time he was initiated into the Nabis along with douard Vuillard Paul S rusier and Bonnard The Nabis which translates as the Prophets based their style subject matters and techniques on the works of Paul Gauguin Vincent Van Gogh Toulouse Lautrec and others The Nabis merged these separate styles into a single defined style that was later taken up by famous artists like C zanne and Matisse He exhibited with the Nabis in the Ambroise Vollard Gallery in Paris in and two years later in the Durand Ruel in the same city In he obtained French nationality The First World War had repercussions on their sales and caused financial problems Vallotton produced several works inspired by the conflict He went to live in Cagnes sur Mer in the winter of In November he was hospitalized and died after an operation for cancer A foundation for the study and promotion of the art of Vallotton was established in Lausanne in Between realism simplified stylisation and bitter criticism of the society of his time F lix Vallotton was above all a tireless worker creating more than canvases and engravings during his life

text: One Day One Dauman Gr ve au Mus e Qui a dit que les gr ves est une tradition fran aise En contre toute attente themuseumofmodernart est historiquement en gr ve Men par le syndicat au nom tr s Pop Art le PASTA aujourd hui momalocal Professional and Administrative Staff Association of the Museum of Modern Art cette gr ve et les manifestations qui l entourent sont une nouveaut New York mais surtout dans le petit monde ferm de l art et encore plus dans le tr s petit monde des mus es C est la premi re fois que le personnel ose une gr ve de semaines A l issue de cet v nement social in dit les employ s ont un nouveau contrat des garanties financi res et surtout une ouverture du mus e qui contredit Maurice Rheims Commissaire priseur embl matique qui disait les mus es sont les glises des collectionneurs En avril le MoMa connaitra sa deuxi me grande gr ve toujours men e par le syndicat activiste PASTA wow moma strike collectors photo unpublished inedit noiretblanc blackandwhite collectingphotography vintagephotography portraitphotography contemporaryphotography celebrityphotography photography artauction photojournalism signed artcollecting henridauman manhattan darkroom buyart buyartonline achat photolovers now lovephoto opportunityStrike at the Museum Who said strikes is a French tradition In against all odds the MoMA was historically on strike Led by the union with the name very Pop Art the PASTA Professional and Administrative Staff Association of the Museum of Modern Art this strike and the street demonstrations are a novelty in New York but especially in the small closed world of the art and even more in the very small world of museums This is the first time the staff has dared a seven week strike At the end of this unprecedented social event employees have a new contract financial guarantees and especially an opening of the museum that contradicts Maurice Rheims iconic auctioneer who said museums are collectors churches In April the MoMA know his second big strike ever conducted by the activist union PASTA

text: As a graffiti artist Jean Michel Basquiat used the name Samo a contraction of same old shit plus the motif of a crown and a copyright symbol He was the king of New York s graffiti scene and then created a furore in the art world In this painting the crown surmounts two skulls That Basquiat was already concerned with the dangers of success in is evident from the text on another painting most young kings get their head cut off Basquiat was initially active in New York s graffiti scene but around the age of twenty he found success in the world of contemporary art His canvases are filled with colourful letters and hieroglyph like signs One recurring and highly personal motif is a skull with a crown and the copyright symbol emblematic of his rapid fame that would prove fatal he died of a heroin overdose at the age of twenty seven Jean Michel BasquiatKings of Egypt II acrylic and oilstick on canvas mounted on wood supports by cm

text: Peter Paul Rubens The Judgement of Paris Oil on Oak On ViewNational Gallery nationalgallery This painting depicts a critical moment in classical mythology The man on the left with his back to us is Paris who had been raised as a shepherd unaware that he was actually a prince of Troy By fateful chance he was asked to judge a beauty contest between three goddesses and to award a golden apple to the winner Although the original story is Greek here we see the Roman version with the goddesses Juno Minerva and Venus who is attended by Cupid To help him make his decision Paris has asked them to undress while each goddess has also offered him a bribe The scene was a popular one among patrons and artists in the seventeenth century Rubens painted it six times including a much later version which is also in the National Gallery s collection It evoked both literary learning and sexual frisson an opportunity to display at least three female nudes in one painting very often from different angles The three women could be shown still competing for Paris attention or reacting to his decision Here Rubens seems to have changed his mind about which moment to depict Via nationalgallery

name: 2019-09-25 02.08.39 2140142756958328607_moma.jpg
text: As a graffiti artist Jean Michel Basquiat used the name Samo a contraction of same old shit plus the motif of a crown and a copyright symbol He was the king of New York s graffiti scene and then created a furore in the art world In this painting the crown surmounts two skulls That Basquiat was already concerned with the dangers of success in is evident from the text on another painting most young kings get their head cut off Basquiat was initially active in New York s graffiti scene but around the age of twenty he found success in the world of contemporary art His canvases are filled with colourful letters and hieroglyph like signs One recurring and highly personal motif is a skull with a crown and the copyright symbol emblematic of his rapid fame that would prove fatal he died of a heroin overdose at the age of twenty seven Jean Michel BasquiatHANNIBAL acrylic and oilstick on canvas mounted on wood supports by cm

text: I don t do much cooking I m an artist I have privileges you see that only men had in the past I worked with Jackson Pollock and Franz Kline on the WPA in the s but I never cooked for them Oh no I wanted to have a man who would cook for me Channeling Alice Neel always in heart as I m realizing that even in accepting spaces my voice in gender revolution is important and I should always be loud about it It s a voice that echos across intersectionalities in a way that I will never wear but always align with as a queer woman and an ally in equity Cooking is not a protest I could ever commit to though just a couple topics I will graze over with kyleealexander on our shemakeschicago podcast dropping this Thursday What s everyone cooking up I m hungry cookingartist feministartist feministartists whatsfordinner feministsofchicago chicagofeminist aliceneel moma chicagowoman bookoftheday cookbookclub

name: 2019-09-25 09.57.38 2140378802429989345_moma.jpg
text: The last couple of months have been a bit of a reality check for me I realized this is John s johnmagz last year being a kid before he turns next year and becomes a teenager Which means my house will be filled with three teenagers oh boy He has grown taller than me and has lost any hint of roundness in his cheeks He laughs at jokes that don t start with knock knock anymore He gets shy when I sing to him Mamai sirun teghikeh Mamai pasha teghikeh And so I have come up with a list of my top things to teach my son before he s a teenager I mean I have instilled some of these habits at a young age but some of these habits need to be remind it Also any moms out here who have teenage boys and would like to contribute to this list please do so Would so love to hear from you Stand up for yourself and what you believe is right It may not always be easy but it will always feel better in the end than sitting back and doing nothing Please do not fart burp or make other disgusting sounds around girls Do not bully others and don t put up with people who try bullying you Trust your gut If it feels like you shouldn t be doing it chances are it is NOT a good idea At some point in life when you are pressured to do something that is dangerous or unacceptable please ask yourself this question what would my dad say or mom If you dwell on the negative things in life that happen you will live an unhappy life Please remember happiness is a choice Always remember your sisters are your forever best friends Never ever raise a hand on a girl Your dad never did and neither have your grandfathers Be a gentleman Respect the ladies Stay humble but confident Never ever forget what dad and I have taught you It might come handy Your dad and I are always here for you No matter what Regardless of what you have going on good or bad I love you I will always love you Always Always Always Keep growing just not too fast and stay cool Johnny boy JohnMagzanyan MommywoodDiaries

text: M O N E T Everyone discusses my art and pretends to understand as if it were necessary to understand when it is simply necessary to love Claude Monet Today s my Dad s birthday and we both love Monet s work I really love the quote above reminds me of how people remember how we make them feel in the end The beauty of this earth makes me feel so grateful to live in such a special place I hope to remember Monet s words as I create my art to do so with a love of the beauty that surrounds me monet claudemonet modernart modernartist museumofmodernart moma momamonet monetwaterlilies waterlilies waterlily lily impressionism impressionistart artistsofinstagram painter paintersofinstagram monetinspiration weekendinspiration creatorlifestyle newyorkcityart frenchart frenchimpressionism motivationalart artisticinspiration inspiringart inspiringartist historicalart

text: NEW YORK Nosotros Nos declaramos oficialmente ENAMORADOS de NY Sea la poca del a o que decidan visitar esta incre ble ciudad les recomendamos estar dispuestos a NO parar un segundo siempre hay algo nuevo por conocer No importa la cantidad de veces que la visiten ni la poca del a o Nosotros preferimos el invierno las decoraciones navide as pistas de patinaje disfrutar un chocolate caliente bien abrigados y recorrer la ciudad ustedes que estaci n prefieren METROCARD Durante nuestra primer visita decidimos sacar una opci n que nos permitiera viajar ilimitada cantidad de veces durante los quince d as que dur nuestra estad a mientras que en nuestras posteriores visitas de menor duraci n optamos por la opci n de pases ilimitados pero por d a Si se fijan en la p gina se detallan las diferentes opciones y a que costo queda el boleto con cada una de ellas Solo tienen que evaluar cual es la que les conviene dependiendo los trayectos que piensan realizar Tomamos esta foto hace poquitos meses durante nuestro ltimo viaje volviendo de Staten Island El ferry que te lleva a este distrito es gratuito sale cada desde la Withe Hall Terminal Manhattan y si tu intenci n es realizar el viaje solo para ver la ciudad desde el agua y acercarte un poco mas a la estatua de la libertad esta es la mejor opci n Fan ticos de UMC SI Es el mismo ferry que aparece en Spiderman De regreso a casa newyork manhattan brooklyn bryantpark centralpark moma met guggenheim timessquare broadway flatiron lowermanhattan wallstreet oneworldtradecenter dumbo williamsburg brooklynbridge bubbagumpshrimp intrepid strawberryfields empirestate topoftherock rockefellercenter radiocitymusichall statenisland madametussauds

name: 2019-09-25 11.46.59 2140433841737928709_moma.jpg
text: TIMES SQUARE Este punto de la ciudad atrae por su encanto y diferencia con el resto del mundo Cientos de carteles adornan e iluminan las calles al punto que de noche vas a pensar que es de d a Si bien hoy es lindo pintoresco y est lleno de cosas para hacer hasta los a os la intersecci n de Broadway y la st era una esquina mas y muy peligrosa por cierto Fue durante la alcald a de Rudolph Giuliani que gracias a su dise o moderno y vanguardista se transform y hoy nadie quiere perd rsela No es noticia que la vida en NY es un tanto cara y el alojamiento en esta zona no es la excepci n nosotros solemos revisar las ofertas que se publican en todas las apps hoteleras son muchas y seguro ya las conoc s y en cuanto vemos que un precio se acomoda a nuestro presupuesto lo sacamos sin dudarlo Nuestros elegidos son Pensilvania Hotel y YMCA Hostel y creanos que si tienen constancia consiguen la noche a muy buen precio Ojo con el alquiler de habitaciones o apartamentos compartidos Si bien utilizamos este sistema de alojamiento en otras partes del mundo y es muy efectivo en NY est prohibido subarrendar una unidad y en muchos casos si bien es gente real quien publica su casa como alojamiento al momento de presentarte no hay nadie que responda por dicha reserva En nuestra ltima visita Fuimos v ctimas de esta estafa y si bien la empresa intermediaria se hizo cargo de los costos nos vimos con las valijas a las hs sin lugar donde dormir PLAN PERFECTO Con un helado en verano y un chocolate caliente en invierno nuestro plan perfecto para terminar el d a es sentarnos en las escalinatas de tkts y disfrutar de semejante vista newyork manhattan downtown lowermanhattan midtown uppereastside theatredistrict brooklyn bryantpark centralpark moma met guggenheim timessquare text: THE HIGH LINE PARK Con mas de km de longitud este parque se construy sobre una antigua linea de ferrocarril la cual dej de funcionar en y durante a os estuvo abandonada En vecinos de Chealse propusieron a la alcald a urbanizar la zona y alejar a delincuencia del barrio En se inaugur el ltimo de tres tramos que en conjunto forman el nico parque elevado de la ciudad Si bien cada tramo tiene un ingreso espec fico recomendamos recorrer el HighLine de punta a punta para no perderse de ning n detalle Lo mejor ser a comenzar en la parte norte st entre la y av Y terminar en la parte sur Goonsevort St de pasadita visitar el Chelsea Market ubicado justo en este lugar Atracciones del parque Montones Comenzando por su dise o y detalles de v as durmientes y dem s elementos propios del ferrocarril hasta murales miradores obras esculturas fachadas y contra frentes de singular arquitectura objetos de dise o puestos de comida una experiencia nica y poco com n Conocimos este parque el mismo a o de su inauguraci n y desde ese momento lo visitamos siempre que podemos Cada vez que lo hacemos encontramos algo nuevo para ver y disfrutar En esta ltima visita nos sorprendimos con la culminaci n de la estructura central del Hudson Yard el Vessel un sin fin de escaleras que suben y bajan y pod s ingresar gratuitamente reserva previa o en la puerta con algo mas de demora newyork manhattan downtown lowermanhattan midtown uppereastside theatredistrict brooklyn bryantpark centralpark moma met guggenheim timessquare broadway flatiron lowermanhattan wallstreet oneworldtradecenter dumbo williamsburg brooklynbridge bubbagumpshrimp intrepid strawberryfields empirestate topoftherock rockefellercenter radiocitymusichall statenisland madametussauds

text: LITTLE ITALY Y CHINA TOWN Estos barrios nunca pasan de moda Sea para disfrutar de un buen plato de pastas o recorrer sus mercados visitarlos es una cita obligada Ubicados en lower side bien cerca de Soho ambos barrios concentran una gran cantidad de inmigrantes los cuales mantienen sus costumbres y dejan ver cuan cosmopolita es esta ciudad CHINATOWN Son mas de mil ciudadanos chinos y descendientes los que viven en la zona que rodea Mott St y que desde el siglo XIX conforman una de las comunidades mas grandes y de cultura mas marcada de la ciudad Si bien en un inicio se consideraba el barrio mas peligroso de Manhattan hoy es un centro tur stico s per concurrido LITTLE ITALY De menor tama o y rasgos no tan marcados esta peque a Italia concentra hoy muy pocos ciudadanos provenientes de este pa s Al rededor de Mulberry St uno puede disfrutar de varias opciones de comida italiana y disfrutar de un aut ntico Expreso esos d as de frio en donde necesit s recargar energ as Conocimos la zona durante nuestra primer visita y debemos reconocer que no volvimos a visitarla Barrios como Tribeca Hell s kitchen Chealse y Wrenwich son hoy los lugares a visitar en la isla Te van a encantar newyork manhattan downtown lowermanhattan midtown uppereastside theatredistrict brooklyn bryantpark centralpark moma met guggenheim timessquare broadway flatiron lowermanhattan wallstreet oneworldtradecenter dumbo williamsburg brooklynbridge bubbagumpshrimp intrepid strawberryfields empirestate topoftherock rockefellercenter radiocitymusichall statenisland madametussauds

text: Don t remember This is from my first art show It was for Rawartist Denver and was an unimaginable success It took a lot of sacrifice from some key people in my life Mainly Aja and E The whole community supported me all the way Now I m doing it on my own I look at this picture every couple months and see happiness radiating I was happy I see all the art that came from nothing that is in homes across the globe I used to think I wish I could get that spark back More recently I realized I m no longer after a spark I paint not an experience but the stored emotion of that experience is released and allowed to flow It took years to be able to express these emotions New experiences different feelings and circumstances will most definitely change my creative output Be patient is what I constantly remind myself art of supertramp mocomuseum rawart rawartist rawartists denver colorado emergingartist popart moma artbasel flaming abstracts abstractart fingerpainter msfighter arttherapy fineart lassiterfineart generalpublic artist instaartist artistoftheday supertramp artshow gallery artgallery

text: MARINA ABRAMOVI The most famous performance artist in the world shone on the cover of the seeallthis summer edition During her retrospective The Artist is Present at the Museum of Modern Art in New York she became a global sensation For three months Abramovi sat every day for eight hours without food water or speaking in a chair in the exhibition space Visitors were encouraged to sit across the table from her an intense experience for both visitor and artist In we dedicated the summer edition of our magazine seeallthis to the often overlooked talent of the art world In this edition we celebrated genius women in art in the build up to the th anniversary of the women s right to vote in the Netherlands in Our women s edition resonated with so many of our readers that we have since begun the pretty brilliant project and are now extending it into an exhibition and a book seeallthiswomen seeallthis artmagazine women art modernart women fountain marinaabramovic artist performanceart museum exhibition artbook guerillagirls marinaabramovic moma performanceart

text: Next week at friezeartfair FriezeMasters Booth F we will present a solo display of drawings by Michael Craig Martin All the works on display come from the artist s personal archive and the presentation will include over works dating from the s to The selection of drawings which have never been offered for sale before will include studies for paintings wall drawings and museum installations The display will offer an unprecedented opportunity to trace the historical development of Craig Martin s familiar vocabulary of objects including chairs globes lightbulbs ladders and umbrellas many of which continue to appear in his current work MichaelCraigMartinStudy for MoMA project Globe Bulb Book Drawer Hand applied black crepe tape on drafting filmPaper and Image x cm

name: 2019-09-25 19.32.20 2140668052529340686_moma.jpg
text: Dark a sutra is the first act of Nasty Temple our project selected for the section An Activism in Design mentored by jerszyseymourdesignworkshop for forecast platform at radialsystem berlin Dark a sutra is a scenography and performance starting from Kar a sutra Mario Bellini s contribution to the polemic exhibition Italy The New Domestic Landscape Part of the performance is the audio of a Bellini s interview in which the architect affirms how the market coopted his car for the future nomad of the Free Love movement thus transforming it in the Multi Purpose Vehicle symbol of the patriarchal family par excellence Dark a sutra has to be seen as a funeral a celebration a sacrifice of the designer as we know it thus accepting the necessity to rethink the designer as a villain an anti hero that can fight the exploitation and cultural appropriation of his practice of resistance This is the act where the designer understands his degenerated nature and sacrifices his ego The darkest desires drive him to a new level of consciousness Thanks to forecast platform radialsystem berlin and all the team for the support Thanks to Jerszy Seymour for the precious support Thanks to questioncollective antoon steenbock peter behrbohm for the exchange and the healthy competitiveness Ph Camille Blake camille blake and Parasite darkasutra karasutra mariobellini thenewdomesticlandscape moma nyk momanyk nasty temple nastytemple parasiteparasite parasite forecast forecatsforum forecastplatform berlin radialsystem performingart theater performance

text: AMERICAN MUSEUM OF NATURAL HISTORY Volvemos a Manhattan para visitar el museo de Historia Natural que se encuentra en el Upper West Side y que desde el a o explora el origen de la vida en la tierra a trav s de diferentes recursos que atraen a grandes y chicos dioremas animales embalsamados f siles rocas meteoritos etc Son mas de millones de piezas las que pertenecen al Museo y que si bien no se exponen en su totalidad por razones l gicas de espacio y tiempo de los visitantes conforman la mayor colecci n museogr fica del mundo Conoc an la expresi n pay us you wish Rige para este Museo y si bien hay un monto estimado de US uno puede abonar lo que pueda para disfrutarlo Incluido en NY PASS Si bien de noche los animales y exibiciones no cobran vida como sucede en la pel cula Una noche en el museo podemos asegurarte que este lugar tiene algo especial y si visit s la ciudad no te lo pod s perder newyork manhattan downtown lowermanhattan midtown uppereastside theatredistrict brooklyn bryantpark centralpark moma met guggenheim timessquare broadway flatiron lowermanhattan wallstreet oneworldtradecenter dumbo williamsburg brooklynbridge bubbagumpshrimp intrepid strawberryfields empirestate topoftherock rockefellercenter radiocitymusichall statenisland madametussauds

text: INTREPID MUSEUM Para poder visitar el portaaviones USS Intrepid utilizado durante la segunda guerra mundial y la guerra de Vietnam solo deben dirigirse al Muelle ubicado en el West Side de Manhattan El mismo fue adem s utilizado en varios programas espaciales y en las labores de rescate del atentado del S y hoy aloja el museo mas grande y completo dedicado al agua aire y espacio del pa s Este museo naval flotante expone el submarino Growler el Concorde de British Airways nico avi n comercial capaz de romper la velocidad del sonido y varias formaciones a reas de gran nivel hist rico Incluido en NY PASS El valor para adultos es de US Este museo nos pareci entretenido y muuuy completo pero si cuentan con poco tiempo en la ciudad no ser a una de nuestras recomendaciones Solo si sos fan tico de la aviaci n y el espacio newyork manhattan downtown lowermanhattan midtown uppereastside theatredistrict brooklyn bryantpark centralpark moma met guggenheim timessquare broadway flatiron lowermanhattan wallstreet oneworldtradecenter dumbo williamsburg brooklynbridge bubbagumpshrimp intrepid strawberryfields empirestate topoftherock rockefellercenter radiocitymusichall statenisland madametussauds

text: MCM YARD SALE AX Chairs available Recovered in supple top grain leather The iconic AX Chair was designed in by the Danish duo Peter Hvidt Orla M lgaard Nielsen and exhibited at MoMA s Good Design show in It features a gorgeous frame of laminated bent beech wood wrapped around a solid mahogany core These chairs were produced by Fritz Hansen in Denmark and built using Hansen s process for laminate gluing which was in turn borrowed from a technique used to make tennis rackets These particular chairs began their lives at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology with vinyl seats and backs They do show wear appropriate for their age and use numerous areas of finish loss small chips cracks significant wear one has veneer chips on back teak panel as is each danishmodern danishchair midcenturymodern danishdesign axchair Hvidtmolgaard peterhvidt danishteak orlamolgaardnielsen fritzhansen moma

text: American artist Marisol Escobar with some of her carved wooden sculptures New York circa Marisol was born in Paris of Venezuelan parents and spent her youth in Los Angeles and Paris studying briefly at the cole des Beaux Arts In she moved to New York City where she studied at the Art Students League and the Hans Hofmann School of Fine Arts From her earliest roughly carved figures she worked mainly in wood In New York she made ties with the Abstract Expressionists Willem de Kooning Franz Kline and Jackson Pollock among them Though she is often associated with Pop art she incorporated many influences into her work folk art pre Columbian art Cubism Dadaism collage and thus defies classification She gained wide recognition in the s for her mixed media figure groups the juxtaposition of blockish inert forms and their painted cast plaster or found object features and accoutrements lend the works a deadpan irony Many of her works depict variations of the family unit

text: MET MUSEUM Recorrerlo en su totalidad es una tarea muy dif cil para hacerlo en un d a casi imposible Son los departamentos que albergan obras de arte del mundo entero y que desde sorprenden a todos por su gran diversidad y calidad Con mas de millones de piezas en su colecci n permanente el MET museum cuenta con un extenso grupo de curadores dedicados a estudiar conservar y restaurar las mismas y poder as manterner el nivel e inter s en los mas de millones de aficionados del arte moderno que lo visitan anualmente Una vez al a o se celebera el Costume Instituto Gala o la Gala del Met un evento ben fico en donde lo fondos recaudados son destinados al Instituto del Vestido Un evento en donde los mejores dise adores muestran sus creaciones en artistas e influyentes de la moda mundial Las Salas de Arte Romano y Egipcio son las mas concurridas Son mas de mil las piezas expuestas en este departamento la mayor a de ellas obtenidas en excavaciones planificadas por el mismo museo El templo de Dendur se lleva todas las miradas newyork manhattan downtown lowermanhattan midtown uppereastside theatredistrict brooklyn bryantpark centralpark moma met guggenheim timessquare broadway flatiron lowermanhattan wallstreet oneworldtradecenter dumbo williamsburg brooklynbridge bubbagumpshrimp intrepid strawberryfields empirestate topoftherock rockefellercenter radiocitymusichall statenisland madametussauds

text: Inner Impulse We ve all been guilty of being impulsive Or in better terms spontaneous as I d like to call it Yes being impulsive can be considered a negative trait but it doesn t need to be as there are many beautiful benefits to it It s that inner impulse that makes one do what they want to take that extra leap of faith minimal regrets and to the point Black and white Clear and precise You might be thinking how the f does this piece resemble impulsiveness Easy The entire piece was spontaneous The wavy lines are our waves of life Happy peaceful calm quirky and groovy But if you look closely the little neutral streaks resemble the chaotic yet beautiful impulses of life Our inner impulse Title Inner Impulse Size x Medium AcrylicStatus For Sale Price Please contact for details artist art painting paint artwork contemporaryart abstract fineart acrylicpainting modernart abstractart soho chelseanyc abstractpainting whitneymuseum artgallery design moma gallery hauserandwirth artsdistrict abstractartist femaleartist artexhibition artcollector nyc dtla globalart artgallery

text: Edward Willis Redfield The Mill in Winter Oil on Canvas On ViewNational Gallery of Art ngadc Edward Redfield painted The Mill in Winter in seven hours on a snowy December day in in Bucks County Pennsylvania Early in the morning he loaded a large fifty by fifty six canvas he called them s into his pickup truck and drove less than a mile from his home to a site near the mill at Centerville The large canvas was hard to maneuver Redfield recalled that he attached crossbars to the backs of the stretchers to be able to transport the big picture more easily But the canvas s size was not the greatest challenge he faced He had to dress in several layers of woolen clothing and heavy boots and wore fingerless gloves to keep warm It was so cold that his paint froze in the tubes You have to reduce with a great deal of oil in order to make it soft enough to manipulate he said It s quite a job to cover a canvas that size with small brushes And mix the many mixes that you make And you are drawing the same time that you are painting The Mill in Winter is painted in a style that parallels the artist s rugged persona The palette is spare Redfield uses a range of dove grays green grays and blue grays pale yellow and lavender to render both the landscape and the mill Thick swaths of paint are brusquely applied coming to together when seen at a distance to create the appearance of a cold still river snow laden trees and a vast expanse of overcast sky Via ngadc

text: IBRAHIM CONLON ARCHITECT designs documents represents approves and builds functional efficient and beautiful buildings of all scales from small simple single housing to large multi storey complex and commercial all over Australia with a focus on NSW Working in contemporary and heritage architecture for over years we believe to understand our modernity we must understand our anciency That is to understand our future we must understand our past With the current global climate phenomena forcing mankind to rethink every aspect of our lives currently and in the future we believe that absolute reduction of our buildings and a focus on an efficient architecture of needs rather than wants is not only a desire but a necessity Certainly less IS more and the best architecture is Less architecture We design with calm quiet still tranquillity reduction minimalism in mind as we believe that any building made without serenity in mind is a mistake Barragan We seek to integrate the Arts and nature into each design with the objective of making each every building a revolution and focus on glass and courtyard buildings that allow light and views to nature Principal Ibrahim Conlon is a registered Architect in NSW Australia and Master of Architecture M Arch graduate from University of Technology Sydney UTS as well as an associate member of ICOMOS Previous to this he completed a Bachelor of Arts Architecture B A Arch from University of Technology Sydney UTS Previous to this Ibrahim was a qualified experienced Architectural Draftsperson Architect Ibrahim ConlonManaging Director Principal ArchitectNominated Responsible Architect under NSW Architect Act Sydney architect architecture amvsociety sydneyarchitect moma mca art modernarchitect serenity lessismore ibrahimconlonarchitect architectureaustralia australianarchitecture
