text: Salzburg Museum Salzburg Austria Carl Spitzweg painting Sonntagsspaziergang in perfect condition after years inside a HAHN PROTECTOR picture case Documenting successful conservation In the painting was dismantled for the first time from the PROTECTOR to document its state while reviewing the detailed condition of the wooden base material and the sensitive paint layer The result was positive The Head of the Conservation and Restoration Department of Salzburg Museum Stefanie Flinsch confirmed that all glued joints remained without change and two small fissures on the right side did not change in width or length After completing the documentation the painting was reinstalled inside the climate case and will be presented perfectly protected inside the HAHN PROTECTOR for future visitors museum museo exhibition gallery artmuseum sculpture louvre contemporaryart moma modernart history berlin igersberlin berlinstagram ig berlin visit berlin germany berlincity diestadtberlin berlinstyle deutschland ig berlincity berlinpage berlincalling historical historic historicalplace historia ancient

text: David Park Canoe Oil on Canvas Sheldon Museum of Art sheldonmuseum David Park decisively influenced the course of Bay Area art in his day by initiating a historic new direction in painting The Bay Area Figurative movement is now considered the area s most singular contribution to th century American art Park moved to Los Angeles in to attend the Otis Art Institute his only formal education but dropped out after less than a year In he began teaching at the California School of Fine Arts now the San Francisco Art Institute and adopted the then dominant mode of abstract expressionist painting Via sfmoma

text: I painted Mars Ascending looking at a print out of Van Gogh s Starry Night I hoped to take the unbridled energy of the God Mars and what I imagined was the wild psyche of Van Gogh and lift in to a place of peace and balance Interesting my man Brian is at the top holding this energy He might call it a self portrait of me My gallery Director in Greece Vassilis taught me my art can speak for itself in ways I could not know And to let it I just enjoy knowing and sharing the process What do you see Show time soon acrylicpainting abstractpainting contemporaryart jung greekmythology mykonos interiordesign moma architecture magazine chearneyart banmanblue

text: Here s what the revered art historian Magnus said about my piece The Great Beyond The artist embodies thirst Thirst for knowledge thirst for truth thirst for freedom The Great Beyond is a meta metaph ironic exposition of the folly of mankind It is in man s nature to be the architect of his own destruction The visionary leading the blind who in turn leads the blind so on so forth until even the blind shall see Alas What does the man gain A peek into the unknown A new paradigm of thought What lies over yonder The artist chalaboycomics invites the audience to engage on this journey where the observer merges with the observed Egad The bells begin to chime singing their melancholic chorus art moma drawing love light freedom miranda jerrysaltz farago sfmoma tate modernart postmodern chalaboycomics lol comedy goat fun picoftheday

name: 2019-09-27 01.24.04 2141569868096604713_moma.jpg
text: In pop artist Robert Indiana created a LOVE series which would become one of his most iconic and recognizable works to date The image of the word LOVE was arranged in a square with LO stacked above VE with a tilted letter O In The Museum of Modern Art selected LOVE for its Christmas card and the work quickly became emblematic of the Love Generation In the United States Postal Service reproduced the image to be used on a stamp and the popularity of the image used in countless iterations since emphasizes how it continues to resonate with audiences In Robert Indiana felt the messaging should read HOPE so he created a series of sculptures paintings and prints based on the word I wanted to help name and empower the next generation and I felt that HOPE encompassed the needs of our time stated the artist It has been years since he created the work and though times have changed drastically we continue as a nation to believe in both HOPE and LOVE This is America robertindiana popart popartist hope america lovetrumpshate andywarhol robertindianadealer popartdealer artadvisory whistleblower barackobama obamacampaign robertindianahope thisisamerica museumofmodernart modernart modernartdealer moma popicon

text: Elegant Lady with a Bouquet of Roses Painted by Emile Vernon Born March Blois France Died January Blois France aged First studied design at the School of Fine Arts in Tours where he won the first prize for design in at the age of sixteen He moved to Paris when he was eighteen to study with the famed teachers and artists William Bouguereau and Auguste Trupheme at the Ecole Des Beaux Arts In he had two exhibitions first he participated at The Exposition of Fine Arts and Decorative Arts in Paris and later the same year exhibited at the Salon des Artistes Francais and from then on Emile Vernon exhibited regularly at the Paris Salon from to Vernon specialised in painting portraits and genre scenes The fact that he mastered the graphics of his work and painted the lighting in a clever seductive manner made his portraits charming and of a very high quality and are much in demand in the America Canada and Japan Emile Vernon also received numerous commissions for decorative murals as well as oil painting for the theater of Chatellerault in He also created paintings for the Nevers Theater In he exhibited at The Royal Academy in London the floral painting Roses Emile Vernon died in at the age of Fig Details museum moma metmuseum museedulouvre britishmuseum nationalgallery museodelprado vangoghmuseum brooklynmuseum artforum artbasel tatemodern instamuseum rijksmuseum whitneymuseum nationalgalleryofvictoria nationalmuseum gettymuseum curator graffiti streetart oilpainting bouquet roses emilevernon blois france yourarttimes

text: Amedeo Modigliani Portrait of Jeanne H buterne Oil on Canvas On ViewThe Barnes Foundation barnesfoundation The model here is Jeanne H buterne Amedeo Modigliani s lover during the last three years of his life H buterne was an art student when she and Modigliani began their relationship in The two lived together in the Montparnasse neighborhood of Paris and she frequently posed for him Though their relationship was often stormy the turmoil never found its way into his paintings instead Modigliani presents his lover as the embodiment of calmness and sensuality drawing inspiration from ancient Greek statuary and African tribal sculpture Via barnesfoundation

text: Scomparso il settembre all et di anni Robert Frank tra i fotografi pi noti della prima met del Novecento La sua opera pi famosa The Americans la serie di immagini pubblicate nel e realizzate nel corso di due anni dall artista il quale grazie a una borsa di studio vinta dalla Fondazione Guggenheim ha la possibilit di trasferirsi negli Stati Uniti Il risultato di oltre scatti la rappresentazione sotto forma di un reportage documentaristico dell immaginario americano degli anni Cinquanta con le sue luci dal glamour di Hollywood al boom economico e alla nascita del consumismo e le sue ombre dalle periferie affollate da emarginati e dalle discriminazioni razziali Le sue opere fanno parte di importanti collezioni museali tra cui il themuseumofmodernart e la National Gallery of Art di Washington artdumonde americanartist robertfrank theamericans moma newyorkcity Washington newyork photography photographer fotografia

text: The hands of one of the greatest to ever wield a chisel Sylvester Mubayi has aptly been described as the greatest stone carver alive His work is included in the permanent collections of the Metropolitan Museum of Modern Art the Rodin in Paris discerning collectors worldwide He has exhibited extensively in Germany Belgium France England the U S Australia and Asia During my first visit to his workshop in Chitungwiza outside Harare Zimbabwe I observed a pile of sculptures in various states of completion I learned that this first generation master never allows a sculpture to leave his workshop unless he is completely satisfied He is the most recognized stone sculptor alive The Hartsfield airport on Atlanta Georgia has in its permanent installation several of his monumental sculptures Hear Sylvesters s own words in a rare interview on Zimstonegallery com and on YouTube Sylvester Mubayi First Generation master stone carver sylvestermubayi zimbabwe shonasculptures masterclass stonecarving zimstonegallery collectable africanart thegreatest blackartgallery legacyartist moma rodinmuseum atlantaairportart

name: 2019-09-27 14.39.51 2141970397493589749_moma.jpg
text: A Girl in the Garden c Painted by Olga Wisinger Florian Born November Vienna Austria Died February Grafenegg Austria aged Oil on canvas x cm Olga Wisinger Florian the most important representative of the Austrian Mood Impressionism Stimmungsimpressionismus was born in a middle class family in Vienna She first studied piano and became a solo concert pianist Her piano instructor was Julius Epstein who was also Gustav Mahler s music teacher at the Vienna Conservatory In her music career ended due to a hand injury She got married shortly after to a pharmacist Franz Wisinger and had a son Oskar in During the mid s Wisinger Florian turned to painting She studied painting with Melchor Fritsch and August Schaeffer and from was the first private student of painter Emil Jakob Schindler Along with Schindler and his disciples Carl Moll Marie Egner and Tina Blau Lang Olga Wisinger Florian made many study trips They famously painted together in the Plankenberg area As of her paintings were regularly seen at annual exhibitions at the K nstlerhaus as well as the Secession As a young painter Wisinger Florian was completely under her mentor Schindler s influence Her painting of light and mood as well as her choice of motifs alleys gardens fields show strong similarities to Schinder s works After breaking with Schindler in Wisinger Florian developed an increasingly more independent style She then used intense colors and moved from realistic landscape expressionism to dynamic landscape and flower images that were ahead of her time Olga Wisinger Florian was one of the most important painters of the century Her social contacts provided her with an elite circle of buyers Vistors to her studio included Archduchess Clothilde Bavaria s Prince Regent Luitpold and the King of Bulgaria Emperor Franz Joseph I purchased one of her paintings In with her vision diminishing Olga Wisinger Florian withdrew from her active social life She died in Grafenegg Lower Austria She received an honorary grave in Vienna s Central Cemetery

text: I like to remind people that there s creativity in so many of the things you do Originally from Michigan Alexa Cummins grew up as an only child in a family where the kitchen table was consistently covered in art projects It was never clear Therefore when she went off to college at michiganstateu she naturally pursued a degree in Art Education Wanting to end up in the NYC area she then moved here to obtain her master s at nyuniversity and just finished school this past May Since then Alexa has supported herself through working as a nanny while she s been looking for jobs in the museum setting A fan of modern and contemporary art who most enjoys the work of Helen Frankenthaler she ultimately hopes to work for themuseumofmodernart Alexa also hopes to continue creating artwork of her own though and does so these days through water color painting often times viewing her pieces as a visual journal of her life we painted the pictures in our hands during our hour together today She also finds creative outlets through other means however including being outdoors which reminds her of home cooking and reading believing that anything we do in life can have an artistic spin to it So nice to meet you alexacummins kfriends hoboken creativity michigan family michiganstate arteducation nyu moma helenfrankenthaler watercolorpainting outdoors cooking reading meetingpeople How we met Alexa came across my project via bwekafe and then DM ed me to meet

name: 2019-09-28 00.40.18 2142272617215097320_moma.jpg
text: Last night while I was scrolling through IG admiring all of your fabulous posts and pics I came across an image from Art X Master which stopped me It was an image of a drawing by Eva Hesse Who I thought So I googled her and was immediately taken by her work In an incredibly short period of time she had quite the varied output So today after my workout I headed up to the gallery showing her drawings Hauser Wirth Walking up Park Avenue I zigged and zagged through the secret service consulate folks and a heavy NYPD presence Ah yes I thought the UN Turning onto th and out of the melee I entered the gallery Why did I make a special trip there today It s because of a drawing that hangs over our kitchen table My daughters and I eat every meal just beneath it It s one of our favorite pieces It s also unsigned Of course There s a name on the back but it s probably a previous owner And so I ve often wondered just who created this work Cy Twombly Willem de Kooning And now I m thinking Eva Hesse I took a few pics from the exhibition and came straight home I ll spend the rest of my day researching and wondering if just maybe we are sitting beneath a masterpiece hkv evahesse hauserandwirth oberlincollege nyc postminimal antiform drawing modernart contemporaryart whitneymuseum moma postminimalism thcentury postwarart surrealism cytwombly conceptualism newyorkartist willemdekooning americanart abstractexpressionism artdealer artcollector livewithwhatyoulove thedrawingcenter hkfa tatemodern formslargerandbolder hauserwirth dreambig

name: 2019-09-28 00.40.22 2142272647212610797_moma.jpg
text: Andy Warhol s Mao Series The idea of creating portraits of Mao Zedong came from Bruno Bischofberger Warhol s dealer who suggested that Warhol create portraits of the most important figure in the th century At the time in Nixon had just made his historic visit to China Shortly after Life magazine stated that Mao Zedong was the most famous person in the world at that time The mass ideology Maoism and Mao s cult like following in Chinese society instantly attracted Warhol His portraits of Mao were the first time Warhol unveiled any political leanings in his artwork Of his interest in Chinese politics Warhol in famously said I have been reading so much about China They re so nutty They don t believe in creativity The only picture they ever have is of Mao Zedong It s great It looks like a silkscreen In the following year the Warhol Mao Series beginning with his first screenprints featuring the Chinese leader copy mao andywarhol popart love like like moma witheymuseum lanza teguise color china arts leader

text: Pierre Alechinsky La Chaleur Naturelle Oil on Canvas Private Collection Pierre Alechinsky Belgian b is a founding member of the CoBrA art movement Known early on in his career for his skills as a draughtsman Alechinsky studied as an illustrator and typographer at the National School of Architecture and Decorative Arts in Paris from to While in Paris Alechinsky met the poet and artist Christian Dotremont and shortly after their meeting the two formed the CoBrA artistic group together with fellow artists Karel Appel and Asger Jorn The name CoBrA was derived from the members hometowns Copenhagen Brussels and Amsterdam the group was formed on the basic principle of the freedom of color and form in art Via artnet com

text: TC Cannon Washington Landscape with Peace Medal Indian Acrylic on Canvas New Mexico Museum of Art newmexicoartmuseum One of the most influential innovative and talented Native American artists of the th century T C Cannon embodied the activism cultural transition and creative expression that defined America in the s and s Cannon s work as an artist poet and aspiring musician is deeply personal yet undeniably political reflecting his cultural heritage experience as a Vietnam War veteran and the turbulent social and political period during which he worked Cannon preferred bold color combinations mash ups between Native and non Native elements and never shied away from the complexity and nuance of identity politics Cannon interrogated American history and popular culture through his Native lens and exercised a rigorous mastery of Western art historical tropes while creating an entirely fresh visual vocabulary Via National Museum of the American Indian

text: Le R ve Henri RousseauDespite regularly painting exotic scenery Rousseau never travelled beyond France He was inspired by the expositions at the Paris Museum of Natural History and the Jardins des plantes However he relied heavily on his imagination to produce exotic content that is surreal bold and almost childlike He didn t study art and began to paint later in life As a result he was not as influenced by the art movements of his time His work is quite entertaining and you can spend some time finding different animals and plants in each Rousseau wrote a poem to accompany this painting it suggests that the woman is having a dream of a snake charmer playing a flute under the moon and trees in the jungle henrirousseau modernart ledouanier modernart rousseau arthistory thedream lereve artlascaotica artgeeks artmuseum moma art weloveart jungle surrealism jungletheme spottheelephant imagination artinfo artinspo dailyartfact snakecharmer moma

name: 2019-09-28 07.19.49 2142473698632827382_moma.jpg
text: This week I crumbled under the pressures of my everyday life Everything piled up and yesterday I broke I opened my Buisness coming up years ago now Long nights in the studio coming home at am working my but off Many nights I miss dinner miss putting my babies to bed So much unseen work so many tears countless cups of teas and toast for dinner My babies are my world my Buisness is also my baby too But this week it all finally got too much when I felt unwell due to the amount I have been juggling everything and I felt so physically drained and sick I let my kids down Luca was late for school milo stayed in his pjs I dropped Luc to school late walked out and just cried I thought about all of the times I ve let them down let them down by not being there for bed time to read them a story the many times he s been late to things or missed a birthday party I thought of all the times I considered myself a bad mum Then Milo giggled and he reminded me of many things That little giggle out of my smiley boys mouth reminded me how happy my boys are It reminded me how excited they both get when I walk though nanny and grandads doors to collect them It reminded me that no matter how busy I am I always manage some time for them even if it s homework or seeing them on my lunch from work So I picked my sorry ass self off the ground and I told myself exactly what I needed to hear and what s true Being a parent is fucking hard But we do what we can and what we need to for our families Every family is different and so is every situation is different Every struggle is different But with every struggle we have there is also a small victory to go along side it So let s hold onto the small medium and big victories we have So all the mommas and poppas no matter what your going though or how fucking shit you day was hold onto your babies smile momvictories harddays momlife mommy moma parenthood

text: One of my favourite designers ever Marc Newson s Orgone Chair simply amazing Art or Furniture maybe both you decide the Orgone chair was designed in by Marc Newson The original design comes from a series of limited edition aluminum furniture designed by Newson in his Paris Studio POD A plastic version suitable for the mass followed after a short time The Orgone chair is a progression of Marc s Lockheed Lounge and reflects Marc s desire to work with an industrial approach Unconsciously I think I started to leave holes and spaces because it seemed to be a workmanship and finishing of the highest quality the inside and vice versa there is a gap where the inside becomes the outer legs inside the shapes About Marc Newson Born in Sydney Australia in Marc Newson spent his childhood traveling in Europe and Asia before studying jewelry and sculpture at the Sydney College of the Arts Still a student he begins to make experiences and experiments in interior design After graduating in he won a scholarship from the Australian Crafts Council and prepared an exhibition including the Lockheed Lounge at the Roslyn Oxley Gallery in Sydney When the Japanese entrepreneur Teruo Kurosaki proposes to produce his projects Marc Newson moves to Tokyo the city where he lives and works from to Here he produces articles such as Orgone Lounge Black Hole Table and Felt Chair which participate in numerous exhibitions in Asia and Europe In Marc Newson opened a studio in Paris and received assignments from prestigious European companies In the mid s Marc Newson also designed a series of restaurants Coast in London Mash Air in Manchester and Osman in Cologne we love this available now marcnewson orgone marcnewsondesign interiordesigner artmoderne interior interiors moma interiorstyle tokyo interiorstyling interiorstylist interiordesign dubai la london newyork interiordesigner losangeles stdibs interiordesigners chairs paris dubai splendidantiques nyc la

text: Young Woman Wearing a Hat Painted by Pierre Auguste Renoir Born February Limoges France Died December Cagnes sur Mer France aged His father was a tailor and Renoir was given an apprenticeship at a porcelain painter He then had the opportunity to study at the Ecole des Beaux Arts He was a fellow student of Monet Sisley and Bazille he went on summer painting trips with them to Chailly and Fountainbleau He studied the eighteenth century paintings in the Louvre and also met Corot Millet and Diaz His art was noted for its vibrant combination of colours In classic impressionist style he avoided rigid lines and merged objects giving a sense of dream like consciousness He also painted many portraits of women often in nude In he visited Algeria and then Italy In Italy he was deeply impressed by the Italian Masters After meeting Cezanne near Marseilles Renoir sought to break away from Impressionism by developing a new structural style of his own Yet he never abandoned his techniques of colour that he learnt during his impressionist period and he developed a combination of classical styles of applying paint with an impressionist perspective of colour In he married Aline Victorine Charigot a dressmaker twenty years his junior Renoir included her in many of his future paintings depicting family life They had three children including Jean Renoir a noted filmmaker Towards the end of the nineteenth century he gained increasing fame and respect In the French state bought one of his paintings At the Piano During the last years of his life Renoir was crippled by text: ALEXIS AKRITHAKIS ON THE MOVEFrom the Zacharias G Portalakis Modern Art Collection portalakiscollection exhibited at the historical museum of crete Crete Dedicated to the important Greek artist Alexis Akrithakis alexisakrithakis in celebration of the th anniversary since his death it is the fourth annual exhibition co organized by the Society of Cretan Historical Studies and the collector Zacharias G Portalakis A retrospective exhibition as it includes paintings constructions collages and drawings spanning the whole of Akrithakis oeuvre from to it features works that have been described as emblematic and fascinating They present us with an anthology of his work his career the essence of this great artist which is intensely present in even the tiniest sketches because he can and does hold the thread Ariadne s thread which will always show him a way out to the light as noted by the art historian Denys Zacharopoulos in his text written for the exhibition and included in the exhibition catalogue artnet gallery contemporarypainting tategallery oiloncanvas modernart abstract artcall artlife expressionist contemporarypainter contemporaryartist artcollector museum nationalgallery artcurator contemporaryartwork london paris greece tatemodern museumday museumday museumlovers artmuseum museumday themuseumofmodernart newyorkart instaart gallerist metmuseum moma

text: Orange Red Yellow is a Color Field painting by Mark Rothko On May it was sold at Christie s from the estate of David Pincus for a record nominal price for post war contemporary art at public auction Souren Melikian of The New York Times described Rothko s Orange Red Yellow as one that can convincingly be argued to be the most powerful of all his pictures Kelly Crow of The Wall Street Journal stated that The painting s trio of orange and yellow rectangles bobbing atop a cherry red background forms a palette that s as eye catching as a sunset or a Popsicle noting that Auction specialists say collectors historically pay more for works that are red and gold as opposed to gray art abstractexpressionism abstractart abstractpainting abstractartist visualart artgallery artlovers artcurator artfair artnews artnet artsy saatchiart fineart moma contemporaryart artforsale contemporary modernart modernpainting artoftheday abstract contemporaryartist artist gallery artmuseum painting artist markrothko

text: Martin Blaszko El gran ritmo Founded in by Margareta and Miklos von Bartha the gallery has specialised in Constructivist and Concrete art from the beginning From Margareta and Miklos von Bartha acquired over works of Argentinian artists from the Arte Concreto and Mad movements in Buenos Aires They published a catalogue which is still considered the standard reference work for this art movement Today these paintings sculptures and works on paper are in major private collections and museums such as eight of the works donated by Patricia Phelps de Cisneros to MoMA New York in including those by Alfredo Hlito Ra l Lozza Tom s Maldonado Juan Mel Gregorio Vardanega and Virgillo Villalba This painting by Martin Blaszko has been shown by von Bartha at Art Basel in and later shown in the exhibition Latin American Artists of the Twentieth Century in at MoMA New York the most extensive survey of modern Latin American art ever assembled The exhibition opened at the Plaza de Armas Seville in August and traveled to Paris where it was shown at both the Musee National d Art Moderne Centre Georges Pompidou and the H tel des Arts in November Its final European viewing was at the Josef Haubrich Kunsthalle in Cologne where it was shown under the auspices of the Museum Ludwig The tour concludes with its New York showing Images Martin Blaszko El gran ritmo Oil on canvas x cm Collection E F Costantini Buenos Aires Latin American Artists of the Twentieth Century installation view MoMA New York von Bartha booth at Artbasel Martin Blaszko in his home in Buenos Aires themuseumofmodernart cppcisneros vonbartha artbasel vonBartha MoMA MartinBlaszko LatinAmericanArt ArteConcreto ArteMadi BuenosAires Constructivism ConcreteArt Cisneros

text: Los amantes de Ren Magritte Es un cuadro del artista belga Ren Magritte de estilo surrealista fue pintado en Par s y pertenece a una de las piezas de la colecci n En el cuadro se puede ver a una pareja besandose con la cabeza cubierta Puede tener varios significados uno es sin conocer la historia del pintor que puede ser el amor prohibido o el amor ciego evadiendo la superfecialidad Otro es que su madre se suicid y cuando sacar n el cadaver del r o tenia la cara cubierta de ello que se preguntan muchos porque en la mayor a de sus pinturas los protagonistas no tienen cara El cuadro se encuentra en el museo de Arte Moderno de Nueva York Lovers by Ren Magritte It is a painting by the Belgian artist Ren Magritte surrealist style was painted in Paris and belongs to one of the pieces of the collection In the picture you can see a couple kissing with their heads covered It can have several meanings one is without knowing the painter s story that can be forbidden love or blind love avoiding superfeciality Another is that his mother committed suicide and when they took the body from the river he had his face covered many of them wonder because in most of his paintings the protagonists have no face The painting is in the Museum of Modern Art in New York

text: The reprinting of the original compact format Complexity and Contradiction coinciding with the book s th anniversary does highlight the critical differences between the edition x portrait format and the edition at x landscape format Interestingly the book was a series of lectures turned into a book which explains a lot about the flow of images and text The original s thumbnail scaled images look like slides and seem determined to foreground the text The edition makes it far easier to appreciate the images especially the drawings Ironically the multiple formats also afflicted Learning from Las Vegas that originally appeared as a large format book designed by Muriel Cooper and was re released as a smaller paperback More on that later complexityandcontradiction robertventuri moma grahamfoundation formatmatters

text: Did you feel lost when you were pregnant I did I doThe idea of being pregnant is hard It s exhausting It s overwhelming It s lonely My first pregnancy was definitely easier than my second I still enjoyed being pregnant even when the symptoms are unbearable Dealing with the mental shift that happens I feel is sometimes more trivial than vomiting all the time Becoming a Mom for the first time is exciting but a part of me was mourning my old life my old self Knowing that becoming a Mother was simply going to out shine anything I had ever done or ever been The unknown is scary there was so much I didn t know This is where I felt isolated and alone I had questions daily What if I don t like being a Mom What if I can t afford my child What happens if I get too sick to take care of my child If you are becoming a new Mom and are reading this please know and understand It s completely normal to feel these emotions and insecuritiesYou are much stronger than you feelYou are doing a fantastic jobIts ok to ask and seek helpThere is support for you You will only GROW and LEARN from becoming a Mom It is a big journey It will not be easy But you will become stronger and stronger everyday The achievement of becoming a Mother will empower you to want to do better each day newmomstribe newlifemom pregnancyguidelines pregnancy andmoms pregnantandperfect otter kids baby lover ohiobabyco babytula baobeimaternity senita sweatandmilk loveandfitshop kimperryco momsandmamas motherhood womenempowerment newmommies newmomtips fitpreggo fitpregnancy selfcare selflove momtruth moma momandbaby momstruggles strongwomenlifteachotherup

text: Si solca il tempo saltando maldestri da un giorno all altro senza margini di contatto evidenti tra le sue frazioni ma paradossalmente anche senza punti di rottura o soluzioni di continuit Abbozzare un sorriso sotto il cielo plumbeo sciogliere l affanno nell uggia delle gocce di pioggia che colano sui vetri illudersi che un orologio rotto segni l ora esatta solo due volte al giorno sono tutti sentori della pretesa degli uomini di dominare il tempo scandirne le dinamiche tuffarsi in un vortice imperituro che contro ogni volont umana e divina resta sempre uguale a se stesso Non si pu dunque stabilire una dialettica del Tempo con un univoco avvicendarsi di tesi antitesi e sintesi L uomo insegue i giorni le ore i minuti per distanziare quanto pi possibile il momento della sua dipartita le divinit invece pur perseguendo il medesimo obiettivo sviliscono il pragmatismo terreno per proiettarlo oltre gli orizzonti temporali eccepibili dal comune sentire questo il senso degli orologi fluidi dipinti da Dal nella Persistenza della Memoria oggi custodito al MoMA di NY la geometria della landa desolata che accoglie quelle lancette sfatte la mosca adagiata sul piccolo orologio giallo in primo piano e le formiche che si accalcano su quello arancio l unico ancora intatto seppur in progressivo diradarsi disegnano l idea di un incontrollabile inganno ordito dal Cosmo a danno e beneficio del Cosmo stesso La tela nasce all apice del Surrealismo e della riflessione filosofica sul Tempo e sulla Psiche basti citare su tutti la psicoanalisi di Freud e la teoria di Bergson che opera una cesura tra Scienza e Coscienza per distinguere le contrastanti percezioni che il tempo restituisce in frangenti differenti della vita Oggi negli stilemi della societ liquida e globalizzata il controllo del tempo esce amplificato dai timori di una connessione che per quanto continua sempre pi priva di tangibile interazione Nel frattempo il volto di Dal divenuto emblema della Resistenza al potere costituito in una serie TV da record che celebra le gesta di una moderna quanto disorientata combriccola di Robin Hood Segno dei tempi mich gregorio

text: Throwback to THEASTER GATES for Line Drawing for Shirt and Cloak on September th regenprojects Regen Projects is pleased to present Line Drawing for Shirt and Cloak the second solo exhibition at the gallery by Theaster Gates Swipe Line Drawing for Shirt and Cloak presents a complex reflection on desire consumption surrender using contemporary activations of the storefront as a vehicle for expressing both emotional and aesthetic intent With a highly honed metal strategy and the artist s ENTIRE wardrobe this multi faceted installation represents a conscious movement toward the freedom found when one s appetite and the world s insistence asks for everything and a moment of clearing when emotive freedom is found Regen Projects Gates had an amazingly beautiful amount of support from some of his closest friends who also happen to be some of the most brilliant artists creative minds in the art world Thelma Golden Mark Bradford Glenn Ligon and Nathaniel Mary Quinn who also just opened his own stunning show at Gagosian in Beverly Hills were all in attendance to celebrate Theaster s latest important thought provoking exhibition On view until November TheasterGates artist art visualart contemporaryart photography dtla fineart sculpture abstractart modernart thebroad robertrauschenberg lacma moca MoMA glennligon thelmagolden markbradford nathanielmaryquinn frieze LA chicago beverlyhills blackisbeautiful architecture hollywood artwork artbasel theastergates milesregis supportlivingartists

text: Paul C zanne Mont Sainte Victoire La Montagne Sainte Victoire Oil on Canvas On ViewThe Barnes Foundation barnesfoundation Mont Sainte Victoire which towered over the Aix en Provence region of southern France was one of C zanne s favorite motifs He spent his childhood exploring its terrain and he painted it several dozen times from different vantage points The mountain also held symbolic meaning to the artist representing the ancient countryside the authentic France during a moment of rapid industrialization and modernization On the right side of the canvas one can just make out an ancient Roman aqueduct Via barnesfoundation

text: Mark RothkoSlow Swirl at the Edge of the Sea Slow Swirl at the Edge of the Sea pictures two creatures dancing between sea and sky surrounded by arabesques spirals and stripes The forms have no direct association with any particular visible experience but in them one recognizes the principle and passion of organisms Rothko said For him art was an adventure into an unknown world like the Surrealists before him Rothko looked inward to his own unconscious mind for inspiration and material for his work Painted during his courtship with his second wife it is likely that Slow Swirl by the Edge of Sea represents Rothko and Mell art abstractexpressionism abstractart abstractpainting abstractartist visualart artgallery artlovers artcurator artfair artnews artnet artsy saatchiart fineart moma contemporaryart artforsale contemporary modernart modernpainting artoftheday abstract contemporaryartist artist gallery artmuseum painting artist markrothko

text: And in the end all that is really leftIs a feeling strong and unavoidable That somehow we deserved something better That somewhere along the line thingsGot fouled up And that letter from whoever s In charge which certainly would have set Everything straight between us and the world Never reached us Got lost somewhere Possibly mislaid in some provincial station Or sent by mistake to an old address Whose new tenant put it on her dresser With the curlers and the hairspray forgetting To give it to the landlord to forward And we still wait like children who have sent Two weeks allowance far away To answer an enticing advertisement From a crumbling yellow magazine Watching through years as long as a childhood summer Checking the postbox with impatient faith Even on days when mail is never brought

text: Absolutely amazing Joe Columbo Boby Utility Cart Originally designed to be used as an addition to drafting tables it soon found itself to be very useful in everyday life Can be used as an end table office cart or even in the kitchen Made of strong ABS plastic which is easy to clean and looks great This piece is part of MoMA s permanent collection and won the SMUA Award in This example is a rarer white version Some yellowing to plastic throughout which is very common for the white but overall in amazing vintage condition All drawers and parts are in perfect working order and this cart is complete Any questions or need for additional photos please DM Measurements tall wide deep Instagram Price OBO based on ZIP code clevelanddrygoods vintageandmodern vintageresale girlboss clevelandvintage vintage cleveland cle clevelandsmallbusiness buyvintage modernvintage vintagestyle vintageshop midcenturymodern vintageseller midcenturyfurnitureforsale midcentury shopvintage etsy etsyseller etsyshop vintagehomedecor midcenturyhome midcenturyfurniture midcenturyart midcenturyeverything joecolumbo bobycart midcenturyutilitycart moma

text: I wrote a fifteen page screenplay for a short that got cut down to three minutes I drew the storyboards shot charts and planned each scene I scouted locations did the cinematography directed and starred in the film because I couldn t find an actor Finally I had to learn a complex editing software DaVinci Resolve to complete my first film It took about five hundred hours to make this three minute short When it was all said and done I was sitting on the stage at LACMA filmmaker shortfilm indiefilm independentfilm director producer screenwriter storyboard movies movietrailers scifi cancer thebeehiveclustermovie film mesafilmfestival raindancefilmfestival artsharela stevengutierrez mural streetart gute dtla everyday dtlaart avantgardeart avantgarde lamag lacma moma MoMA moca thebroad fineart contemporaryart lacma themuseumofmodernart mocalosangeles thebroadmuseum lacma

text: Artist DEVIN B JOHNSON Throwback to Saturday Sept st On view until Nov th Residency Art Gallery is beyond ecstatic to present The Atmosphere of Certain Uncertainty a solo exhibition from Brooklyn based LA born Devin B Johnson his first solo SOLD OUT showing after completing his MFA at Pratt Institute in May The new collection of work was created in response to Franz Fannon s novel Black Skin White Masks in which Fannon attempts to break down and conceptualize the contemporary black male psyche Johnson metaphorically reinterprets the white mask as white socks that serves as a reminder of that assimilation we walk into everyday just as much as the mask as implied by Fannon ARTIST NOTES For me the contrast of white against black skin speaks to a type double consciousness we navigate through everyday In the series White Nike Socks on Black Skin I simply wanted to attach these concepts ideas to a classic LA convention such as slides and socks The bodies presented in the work are always a non violent body a body that just wants to simply be FUN FACT Johnson has been chosen as one of the official selection of artists for the inaugural year of Black Rock Senegal the artist in residence program developed by multi disciplinary Obama portrait artist Kehinde Wiley Between August April Black Rock will host international multi disciplinary artists to live work in Dakar Senegal on the Westernmost point of continental Africa DevinBJohnson artist fineart contemporaryart visualart LA inglewood dtla blackisbeautiful prattinstitute nyc brooklyn losangeles portraiture painting beverlyhills lacma moca MoMA artoftheday artwork frieze artbasel thebroad henrytaylor markbradford residencyart kehindewiley devinbjohnson nicodimgallery blackrocksenegal supportlivingartists Atmosphereofcertainuncertainty

text: Julia Margaret Cameron c Painted by George Frederic Watts Born February Marylebone Middlesex England Died July Compton Surrey England Oil on canvas cm Watts was frequently ill during childhood and spent a great deal of time in bed drawing stories for himself His first major success as painter took place in the spring of Watts entered the competition for the decoration of the Houses of Parliament and won the prize of for his drawing of Caractacus led Captive through the Streets of Rome He brilliant depiction of historical personalities impressed the judges and set the stage for a lucrative art career His fellow competitors included historical painter Benjamin Haydon Haydon whom was beset by financial difficulties became so upset over the younger artists win that he took his own life Watts used his winnings to travel to Italy According to Art historian William Loftus Hare Italy and particularly Florence was perpetual fascination and inspiration to Watts There he imbibed the influences of Orcagna and Titian In Watts fell in love with a beautiful young actress young enough to be his daughter The artist courted Miss Ellen Terry with old fashioned gallantry and road to her home on a white horse begging her to marry him Terry was impressed with the art and elegance of his lifestyle and wished to please her parents by making an advantageous marriage They married on February shortly before her th birthday when Watts was Terry and Watts were separated after only ten months of marriage during which she took a break from the stage returning by The great artist was variable and uncertain Though humble and self deprecatory to an extreme degree he made mistakes from which he could escape only with great difficulty and he suffered much from depression and melancholy The aging painter continued to earn great renown for his luminous portraits and monumental allegorical paintings Towards the end of his life Watts gave most of his work to British museums Fig Details

text: Convergence by Jackson Pollock Perhaps his most famous work was a painting entitled Convergence which was a collage of colors splattered on a canvas that created masterful shapes and lines that evoke emotions and attack the eye The painting was created in and is oil on canvas inches by inches With Pollock s brushstrokes he was able to make handy use of colors lines textures lights and contrasting shapes This painting is enormous and its size can only really be appreciated in person Searching for something to follow his drip paintings Pollock began working in black and white which is the way Convergence began Not happy with the result he added color as a way to salvage the work In critics debated whether or not he had succeeded Today however Convergence is considered one of the artist s masterworks art abstractexpressionism abstractart abstractpainting abstractartist visualart artgallery artlovers artcurator artfair artnews artnet artsy saatchiart fineart moma contemporaryart artforsale contemporary modernart modernpainting artoftheday abstract contemporaryartist artist gallery artmuseum painting artist jacksonpollock

text: In MichaelCraigMartin created a site specific installation themuseumofmodernart New York as part of Projects He was invited by the museum to create a walldrawing for their room dedicated to the project On a preliminary visit to the space he was struck by the classical nature of the space one long wall feet flanked by two smaller walls each feet long a configuration similar to the Renaissance monastic refectories where one might typically find a fresco such as TheLastSupper For this project he proposed to make a work in three parts in which two smaller drawings would flank a main one The pictured drawing is one of several studies for the final installation At FriezeMasters we are presenting a solo display of drawings by Michael CraigMartin which come directly from the artist s personal archive and have never been offered for sale before Craig Martin will also recreate one of his earliest wall drawings as part of the display Visit us on Booth F at Frieze Masters London from October friezeartfair MoMA study IIf Hand applied black crepe tape on drafting film x cm

text: Pablo Picasso Gertrude Stein New York not on display Midnight in Paris Gertrude Stein with her portrait This is an example of Picasso s pre Cubist works Look at her mask like face and heavy lidded eyes The painting bears witness to the influence that African sculptures has had on Picasso Gertrude Stein was an American expatriate and writer in Paris She was quite a figure in the early th century Parisian art community Her weekly salon in her apartment rue de Fleurs was frequented by writers and artists such as Ernest Hemingway Scott Fitzgerald Henri Matisse Salvador Dal In fact she is often credited for inventing the expression The Lost Generation In Woody Allen s Midnight in Paris the protagonist Gil Pender was introduced to Stein Kathy Bates and Picasso Marcial Di Fonzo Bo in a room this very portrait was hanging The broader art family always refers to other About those masterpieces in masters movies GertrudeStein picasso pablopicasso portrait art woodyallen midnightinparis moma newyork precubist thcentury parisian thelostgeneration

name: 2019-09-30 18.30.32 2144260834616169133_moma.jpg
text: A BLANK CANVAS Where each Architectural project starts The most important stage in every project where theoretical thought discussion debate testing then re thought re discussion re debate occurs This particular project is a large addition to a late Victorian dwelling in a heritage conservation zone with a beautiful large rear landscaped yard So as an Architect where does one start Gehry says that the start is the hardest part but then you start and it s as if it always was to be Murcutt says he gets very nervous at the beginning of every project and rightly so As every design decision has large consequences on many things The question being is what is really NEEDED vs what is WANTED We have a beautiful natural landscape perfection as it is How can we impose our wants onto such a setting What do we really need to live YES we need shelter We need to protect against the rain weather We need spaces to sleep to cook to eat to relax in to study in Or do we such are the debates in every blank canvas Architects hold this key in our hands Our decisions our principles determine our built environment and affect our environment Bit above all it is the realm of the aesthetic of paramount importance What can be The vision Imaginations of new ways of living The potential The stored energy of possibility THAT is architecture It is my response that the land is PERFECT the way it is and every wall every roof every thing we build is a step backwards Thus the key is to REDUCE the needs and wants Reduce the architecture so the building is like a mathematical equation reduced to its very lowest refined format That is architecture The POSSIBILITY Architect Ibrahim ConlonManaging Director Principal ArchitectNominated Responsible Architect under NSW Architect Act Sydney architect architecture amvsociety sydneyarchitect moma mca art modernarchitect serenity lessismore ibrahimconlonarchitect architectureaustralia australianarchitecture

text: Leslie Hewitt Riffs on Real Time chromogenic color prints in x in each The Museum of Modern Art New York My first love is sculpture And even though I don t work as much in sculpture right now it s particularly in my mind when I produce an autonomous object or image and it is a completely seductive way of working As soon as a child breathes air hears sound and opens her eyes the next stage in development is to touch things and try to make sense of the physical world not just of images Sculptures live in that space of wonder and gravity I think it s important to stress my first impression of these mediums because at some point it became crucial for me to grapple with both sculpture and photography Leslie Hewitt Credit Mousse Magazine LeslieHewitt BlackandBlueChip

text: KARA WALKER A HISTORY OF VIOLENCE Today on The Thread Click on link in bio for full article The silhouette says a lot with very little information but that s also what the stereotype does Brutal shocking and filled with tragedy kara walker official re telling of black history aims for the jugular The artist made her name with cut out silhouettes illustrating bloody violent acts inflicted upon America s black population particularly women during the American Civil War Many of the stories she unearths and spreads across gallery walls in all their theatrical horror are ones history has tried to forget including public lynching sexual assaults and shootings while innocent helpless children look on signalling the wounds inflicted on generations that followed Undoubtedly such controversial material has had its detractors but Walker is deliberately stirring up uncomfortable feelings about deeply embedded cultural trauma and pervasive racism that should not be brushed under the carpet as she explains It makes people queasy And I like that queasy feeling Image Kara Walker fabricsstorecom karawalker womeninart modernart tatemodern textiledesign art wallpaper embroidery textile craft arthistory moderncraftsman painting moderncraft artist art moma maker makersgonnamake ethicalfashion modernweaving weaving nataliagoncharova barbarahepworth georgiaokeeffe rachelryusch vickenparsons marycassatt marlenedumas greatwomenartists

text: FS COLOR SERIES AUTUMN GOLD INSPIRED BY JOHANNES VERMEER S INTIMATE LIGHT A NEW article on The Thread Vermeer was a master of understatement crafting exquisite enigmatic beauty from quiet scenes of domestic life AUTUMN GOLD linen s warm indulgent tone takes its cue from the golden light that ignites these hushed interiors and makes them shine with the gloss of precious metal Strategically placed strands of complimentary colours including Delft blue and china white allow yellow tones to resonate and sing out even brighter transforming ordinary interiors into magical places of silent wonder Artist Irwin Greenberg observed Vermeer found a life s work in the corner of a room To read full article please follow link in bio fabricsstorecom jmwturner impressionism tatemodern textiledesign embroidery textile craft arthistory moderncraftsman postimpressionism painting landscapepainting moderncraft artist art moma maker makersgonnamake isew memade ethicalfashion textile slowfashion modernweaving embroidery embroideryart weaving

text: super rare incised biomorphic pottery lamp by Chicago WPA ceramicist Eugene Deutch signed dated Instagram special rough brown pottery with incised white hatch marks gorgeous American studio potter Eugene Deutch was born in Budapest Deutch left Hungary in and moved to France briefly studying sculpture under Brancusi Four years later he moved to Chicago and in opened his first studio Ceramic Atelier Though Deutch was able to earn a living as a functional potter his finest vessels were more experimental and personal This simple undulating form demonstrates Deutch s strong modernist aesthetic and his mastery of the medium ceramic base inches tall height to top of finial is inches top vertical rod with the sockets is adjustable to includes a new linen shade diameter x tall WPA eugenedeutch lewisinstitute newbauhaus MidwestDesignerCraftsmen moma biomorphic americandesign artpottery lamp ceramiclamp stdibs midcentury midcenturymodern thcenturydesign interiordesign danishmodern scandinaviandesign scandinavian modernism modernist interiordesign losangeles FOR SALE message me for inquiries questions additional photos

text: SELFIES EN EL MUSEO DE SAN JUAN DE LA MATASantalla StrartS y QuinSan han creado la Asociaci n de Museos Virtuales cuyo fin es que todos los pueblos independientemente de su poblaci n puedan disponer de un museo de arte El lema es NING N PUEBLO SIN MUSEO Una vez inaugurados podr n programarse exposiciones temporales o permanentes Los tres primeros museos ya se han inaugurado en Lapuebla de Labarca en San Juan de la Mata y en Madrid y continuar n en Ponferrada Alovera Arganza Sancti Petri Vitoria Trillo SELFIES IN THE MUSEUM OF SAN JUAN DE LA MATASantalla StrartS and QuinSan have created the Association of Virtual Museums whose goal is that all peoples regardless of their population can have an art museum The motto is NO PEOPLE WITHOUT MUSEUM Once opened temporary or permanent exhibitions may be scheduled The first three museums have already opened in Lapuebla de Labarca in San Juan de la Mata and in Madrid and will continue in Ponferrada Alovera Arganza Sancti Petri Vitoria Trillo selfies reinasofiamuseum museodelprado caixaforum museothyssen hermitagemuseum whitneymuseum centrepompidou nationalgallery moma museedorsay louvre met britishmuseum tatemodern guggenheim nycart brooklynmuseum lacmamuseum gemaldegalerie artinstitutechicago ufizzi louvreabudhabi yaleartgallery galleriaborghese gettymuseum sfmoma nationalgalleryofart altepinakothek rijksmuseum

text: J M W Turner Snow Storm Steam Boat off a Harbour s Mouth Oil on Canvas On LoanKunstmusuem Luzern kunstmuseumluzern Turner painted many pictures exploring the effects of an elemental vortex Here there is a steam boat at the heart of the vortex In this context the vessel can be interpreted as a symbol of mankind s futile efforts to combat the forces of nature It is famously said that Turner conceived this image while lashed to the mast of a ship during an actual storm at sea This seems to be nothing more than fiction but the story has endured as a way of demonstrating Turner s full blooded engagement with the world around him Via tate

text: Design Development Modernist pavilion addiction A blank canvass deflorated IBRAHIM CONLON ARCHITECT designs documents represents approves and builds functional efficient and beautiful buildings of all scales from small simple single housing to large multi storey complex and commercial all over Australia with a focus on NSW Working in contemporary and heritage architecture for over years we believe to understand our modernity we must understand our anciency That is to understand our future we must understand our past With the current global climate phenomena forcing mankind to rethink every aspect of our lives currently and in the future we believe that absolute reduction of our buildings and a focus on an efficient architecture of needs rather than wants is not only a desire but a necessity Certainly less IS more and the best architecture is Less architecture We design with calm quiet still tranquillity reduction minimalism in mind as we believe that any building made without serenity in mind is a mistake Barragan We seek to integrate the Arts and nature into each design with the objective of making each every building a revolution and focus on glass and courtyard buildings that allow light and views to nature Principal Ibrahim Conlon is a registered Architect in NSW Australia and Master of Architecture M Arch graduate from University of Technology Sydney UTS as well as an associate member of ICOMOS Previous to this he completed a Bachelor of Arts Architecture B A Arch from University of Technology Sydney UTS Previous to this Ibrahim was a qualified experienced Architectural Draftsperson Architect Ibrahim ConlonManaging Director Principal ArchitectNominated Responsible Architect under NSW Architect Act Sydney architect architecture amvsociety sydneyarchitect moma mca art modernarchitect serenity lessismore ibrahimconlonarchitect architectureaustralia australianarchitecture

text: Tableware and Fruits c Painted by Henri Matisse Born December Le Cateau Cambr sis France Died November Nice France aged Oil on canvas cm Location The State Hermitage Museum Saint Petersburg Henri Matisse is widely regarded as the greatest colorist of the th century and as a rival to Pablo Picasso in the importance of his innovations He emerged as a Post Impressionist and first achieved prominence as the leader of the French movement Fauvism Although interested in Cubism he rejected it and instead sought to use color as the foundation for expressive decorative and often monumental paintings As he once controversially wrote he sought to create an art that would be a soothing calming influence on the mind rather like a good armchair Still life and the nude remained favorite subjects throughout his career North Africa was also an important inspiration and towards the end of his life he made an important contribution to collage with a series of works using cut out shapes of color He is also highly regarded as a sculptor According to David Rockefeller Matisse s final work was the design for a stained glass window installed at the Union Church of Pocantico Hills near the Rockefeller estate north of New York City It was his final artistic creation the maquette was on the wall of his bedroom when he died in November of Rockefeller writes Installation was completed in Matisse died of a heart attack at the age of on November He is interred in the cemetery of the Monast re Notre Dame de Cimiez near Nice museum moma metmuseum museedulouvre britishmuseum nationalgallery museodelprado vangoghmuseum brooklynmuseum artforum artbasel tatemodern instamuseum rijksmuseum whitneymuseum nationalgalleryofvictoria nationalmuseum gettymuseum curator graffiti streetart oilpainting tableware fruits henrimatisse lecateaucambresis nice france rockefellercenter yourarttimes

text: what do we really NEED to live on a land and that is the fundamental question of architecture It forces us to confront our desires hopes wants needs It forces us to question our possessions and way of living and THATS what I love to do I like to see people live simply with less Less clutter less possessions more reflection more looking to nature From such spaces comes truly marvellous architecture The architecture of emptiness stillness reflection and serenity The building there on takes on its own mysterious mechanism to enable reflection and calmness and change far beyond the living room bedroom functions it holds The building becomes a piece of Art and THAT is my objective with every project Architect Ibrahim ConlonManaging Director Principal ArchitectNominated Responsible Architect under NSW Architect Act Sydney architect architecture amvsociety sydneyarchitect moma mca art modernarchitect serenity lessismore ibrahimconlonarchitect architectureaustralia australianarchitectureib

text: In Proportional Notation is the earliest surviving score for Cage s silent piece first performed by the pianist David Tudor in Woodstock New York on August Whereas the lost original score used conventional musical notation to signify three periods of silence this score is composed of a series of vertical lines The duration of the three movements corresponds to the distance between the lines equating spatial and temporal measurements During the premiere Tudor sat quietly at his piano opening and closing the keyboard lid to mark the progression of the three movements The audience waited in anticipation of the performance their expectations of a conventional concert were shattered but music was made Cage recounted You could hear the wind stirring outside during the first movement During the second raindrops began pattering the roof and during the third people themselves made all kinds of interesting sounds as they talked or walked out Cage saw silence as a way to plug the audience into the sound track of everyday life to open them up to the infinite possibilities of ambient sound Cage dedicated In Proportional Notation the second iteration of his silent piece to his friend Irwin Kremen and gave it to him on his twenty eighth birthday in https www moma org collection works modernmarimba moma johncage silence johncage woodstock davidtutor

text: Automatic Drawing Andr Masson Andr Masson began automatic drawings with no preconceived subject or composition in mind Like a medium channeling a spirit he let his pen travel rapidly across the paper without conscious control He soon found hints of images fragmented bodies and objects emerging from the abstract lacelike web of pen marks At times Masson elaborated on these with conscious changes or additions but he left the traces of the rapidly drawn ink mostly intact moma modernart contemporaryart artgallery oilpainting surrealism renemagritte lovers mmoma modernartmuseum

name: 2019-10-02 00.21.27 2145162233083980231_moma.jpg
text: DISCOVER WHAT MADE THE FUTURE Charles and Ray EamesOne of the true power couples in design Charles and Ray Eames were industrial designers best known for their furniture notably the Eames Lounge Chair which just screams s corner office The Eames Lounge Chair and ottoman are permanent pieces in the Museum of Modern Art Charles and Ray were widely talented individuals and had stints in graphic design fine art film and made influential contributions to the fields of design and architecture Charles took on most of the public facing roles but everyone in the Eames team contributed meaningfully Some of the big names coming out of the Eames office were the likes of Henry Beer Richard Foy Annette Del Zoppo Deborah Sussman and so many more Thirteen hour days were the norm which makes it no surprise that their work became highly regarded for its attention to detail and quality The philosophy that drove many of the couples projects was to learn by doing which was evident in their preference for collaboration In the couple used their understanding of furniture design to create splints from furniture material to make an alternative to the metal splints that were causing health issues in the war The Arts Architecture magazine started a Case Study program that has yielded many classics one of which being the Eames House It was hand constructed and made from prefabricated steel parts that were intended for industrial construction The house was designated a Historic Landmark in and is one of the cornerstones of modern architecture and design The couple used short films to record their interests some intellectual and others experimental One of their most fascinating exhibitions called Mathematica is well worth your time More on https www everything com industrialdesign charlesandray eames everything design everything people e everything design moma eameshouse couple

text: God Space Invader NYC Space Invader Series is a Dis Installation metropolitanmuseum a series of photographs as a comment on the dark times we are living today For each picture I chose a John Lennon s song as a title and a link to the actual song as an invite for the viewer to see and listen at the same time A WATCH Despite the fact that most of us have heard them all and seen most of those paintings I believe when seen together it will surprise ones pre judgements changing its perception A SHIFT ON THE CONCEPT The absolute possibility of Dis Understanding it s not about misunderstanding it s about being understood in ways we do not really mean or maybe we do mean it s about THE CHANCE OF PLAYING finite and infinite GAMES contemporaryart reyzorro whitecubegallery artnyc moma whitecube whitechapelgallery gagosian themet liquidskydsign saatchigallery miamibasel serpentineuk tatemodernmuseum tatemodern tatemodernlondon haywardgallery barbicancentre pacegallery artsy londonartwalk thefallmag artmazemag biennial museumofmodernart tatebritainmuseum NewMediaArt fashion art

text: oh the things you can think of if only you try Before kids and even when my first one was born I ve always thought I would choose career for my kids I d put all knowledge and efforts required for it to happen How little did I know Kids are growing and so do parents Right now I came to the point that I want them to be whoever they want I want them to imagine their perfect life and follow it Let them be as crazy with their dreams as possible I want them to be sincerely happy Do you guys plan any life moments or careers for your kids Love those restless minds mother mommy mama mom moma moms madre maman momlife momlifebelike momlifeisthebestlife momliferocks momming motherhood motherhoodunplugged motherhoodsimplified motherhoodslens honestmotherhood momblogger mombloggers momblog mommyblogger mommyblog photography familyphotography

text: Piet Mondrian Composition with Blue and Yellow Oil on Canvas On ViewPhiladelphia Museum of Art philamuseum This composition displays the hallmarks of the classic Mondrian style black lines at right angles and rectilinear planes of intense primary colors that contrast with areas of what Mondrian referred to as non color white gray or black He considered these the most fundamental elements of painting He also thought them as the most universal allowing him to address a higher reality far beyond the ordinary world Via philamuseum

text: H Connectus Series v thru v My kids call these my creepy heads and always ensure my office door is closed before their friends visit lest we traumatise the visitors I call these my version of artistic commentary on the utopian dystopian state of new technologies currently being developed in Silicon Valley beyond From the dawn of time humans have always co evolved with technology Humans create new technologies stone tools the wheel cars planes vaccines social media etc and in return those technologies change us by allowing us to do and accomplish previously impossible things but soon new technologies e g CRISPR nootropics will be able to change humans in the most fundamental of ways genetically which is kinda exciting and scary at the same time Without a doubt there are exciting times ahead in the meantime it s fun using art to explore and communicate some of these complex ideas feelinglucky havingfun keepingitreal artist art modernart abstractart contemporaryart conceptualart instaart artsy abstracto stayabstract instaabstract artoftheday artwork crispr moma transhumanism evolution artificialintelligence technology future singularity saatchi

text: Darial Gorge c Painted by Ivan Aivazovsky Born July Feodosia Crimea Ukraine Died May Feodosia Crimea Ukraine Oil on canvas cm Famous Armenian painter who knew the sea and loved it sincerely Drawing ability of young Aivazovsky attracted the attention of A Kaznacheyev the town governor who helped Aivazovsky to enter the high school at Simferopol and in the St Petersburg Academy of Arts At the age of twenty he graduated from the Art Academy of St Petersburg with a gold medal At the age of he have already gained international fame During the period of Aivazovsky as a pensioner of the Academy of Arts spent time in Italy traveled to Germany France Spain and Holland He worked much and had many exhibitions meeting everywhere with success He painted a lot of marine landscapes which became very popular in Italy Aivazovsky s name is intricately bound with the sea Perhaps no one in Europe has painted the extraordinary beauty of the sea with so much feeling and expressiveness as Aivazovsky has writes V Adasov When in the artist returned to St Petersburg he was awarded the title of Academician and became attached to the General Naval Headquarters This allowed him to travel much with Russian fleet expeditions on different missions he visited Turkey Greece Egypt America From to he painted several canvases with naval warfare as the subject the pictures portrayed historical battles of the Russian Fleet Neither financial security nor life in Palace interested him He returned to his native land built a workplace home on the seashore and until the last days of his life dedicates himself to the work that he loved Aivazovsky left more than pictures Most of his works are world famous museum moma metmuseum museedulouvre britishmuseum nationalgallery museodelprado text: GENIUS WOMEN CHANTAL AKERMAN In her work the Belgian director presents an alternative perspective on females and the feminine This technique becomes apparent in the classic Jeanna Dielman Quai du Commerce Bruxelles The camera does not lust for the female body but instead creates through a distant and static perspective a space for the protagonist which is free from sexual motives A woman peeling potatoes Endlessly A woman washing herself In real time Through which this also becomes common practice Dana Linssen wrote more about the female gaze in See All This magazine available in our web shop Link in bio In we dedicated the summer edition of our magazine seeallthis to the often overlooked talent of the art world In this edition we celebrated genius women in art in the build up to the th anniversary of the women s right to vote in the Netherlands in Our women s edition resonated with so many of our readers that we have since begun the pretty brilliant project and are now extending it into an exhibition and a book seeallthiswomen seeallthis artmagazine women art modernart women fountain chantalakerman director film movies femalegaze womeninfilm femaledirectors artist performanceart museum exhibition artbook guerillagirls moma performanceart

text: EXHIBITION EMMA KUNZ For all those who missed Emma Kunz s Visionary Drawings in the Serpentine Gallery serpentineuk in London there s a second chance to see her work at Muzeum Susch muzeumsusch deep in the Swiss mountains Kunz was mainly active as a healer focusing on the wellbeing of the body and soul using her drawings in healing rituals From Kunz began making her pendulum drawings drawings which she created by use of a pendulum on a chain A technique where upon asking a question a pendulum would guide Kunz s pencil over squared paper Kunz believed that the answers to all questions lay in the geometric shapes created this way In we dedicated the summer edition of our magazine seeallthis to the often overlooked talent of the art world In this edition we celebrated genius women in art in the build up to the th anniversary of the women s right to vote in the Netherlands in Our women s edition resonated with so many of our readers that we have since begun the pretty brilliant project and are now extending it into an exhibition and a book seeallthiswomen seeallthis artmagazine women art modernart women fountain emmakunz geometry artist museum exhibition artbook guerillagirls moma drawing

text: Ticket To Ride Space Invader NYC Space Invader Series is a Dis Installation metropolitanmuseum a series of photographs as a comment on the dark times we are living today For each picture I chose a John Lennon s song as a title and a link to the actual song as an invite for the viewer to see and listen at the same time A WATCH Despite the fact that most of us have heard them all and seen most of those paintings I believe when seen together it will surprise ones pre judgements changing its perception A SHIFT ON THE CONCEPT The absolute possibility of Dis Understanding it s not about misunderstanding it s about being understood in ways we do not really mean or maybe we do mean it s about THE CHANCE OF PLAYING finite and infinite GAMES contemporaryart reyzorro whitecubegallery artnyc moma whitecube whitechapelgallery gagosian themet liquidskydsign saatchigallery miamibasel serpentineuk tatemodernmuseum tatemodern tatemodernlondon haywardgallery barbicancentre pacegallery artsy londonartwalk thefallmag artmazemag biennial museumofmodernart tatebritainmuseum NewMediaArt fashion art

text: Dutch Interior by Joan Mir c Sketch for Dutch Interior Dutch Interior by Martensz Sorg th CenturyA few months prior to the beginning of this painting Joan Mir bought a postcard reproduction of the work by the th century Dutch artist Hendrick Martensz Sorgh depicting a lute player in a domestic interior Using pure flat colours and abstract forms Mir greatly accentuated some elements of Sorgh s composition particularly the lute the man s head and the ruffled collar while diminishing others This ability to break the model by distorting the images is a key characteristic of Mir s style art europeanart artists artwork musee artist museum masterpiece arthistory poetry culture picoftheday inspiration poetry creative imagination artgallery joanmiro artistic mistery fauvism surrealism abstract spain moma abstract

name: 2019-10-02 22.59.58 2145845997211975248_moma.jpg
text: Nello and Patrasche A Dog of Flanders Nello and Patrasche is without a doubt the most beautiful story about Flanders the Dutch speaking part of the little country Belgium in Europe Nello is a young orphan who has an incredible friendship with a street dog named Patrasche Both of them are homeless and they stay a lot in the cathedral of Antwerp where they admire the works of Rubens the world famous painter After a series of mishaps both day on Christmas Eve from starvation and the freezing temperature The cathedral which was the only home they have ever known becomes the spot where they take their farewell from this cruel world together as always like the undivided friends they were It is perhaps one of the saddest Christmas stories in the whole world but people are touched by this story even until today Based on a true story The story unfolds in the towns of Antwerp and Hoboken in Flanders The Flemish artist Batist Vermeulen was asked by the city of Antwerp to sculpt a statue in remembrance and celebration of this story and the protagonists In the endearing statue was erected in the shadow of the cathedral and is a tribute to Nello and Patrasche who really lived and died there but it is also a reminder that there is nothing worse than loneliness and that there is even in the st century ugly things like poverty and abandoned people in our societies This atypical Christmas story has captured the hearts of many people especially in Japan where this story is the most told story to the youth The mix of true friendship unconditional love and a tragic end is what great stories are all about The artist Vermeulen has captured not only the spirit of the story but also the atmosphere of Flemish traditions Historical evidence proves that both Nello and Patrasche were real The people of Antwerp have closed them in their hearts for centuries The statue is a fitting modern structure to an ancient story and it shows that emotions are timeless The pavement that is upon them as a blanket is symbolic of the city of Antwerp covering them with their respect and love Big stories are sometimes found in little corners

text: Panels for Edwin Campbell Vasily KandinskyA year earlier Kandinsky had begun to use the term nonobjective painting referring to art that depicts nothing in particular MoMa reference These panels reflect that Kandinsky was among the first ambassadors of the abstract movement He was deeply inspired by the ability of music to produce images in the mind and he sought a similar effect in his art For him abstract art was the best medium for transmitting emotions Edward Campbell was the founder of Chevrolet and these panels total were commissioned for his home Pictured are panels and This picture is not the best but it fits the panels we like best vasiliykandinsky kandinsky modernart abstractart nonobjectiveart louisvuittonfoundation MoMa paintingsatmoma artmuseum russianart artlascaotica artlas art arthistory derblauereiter bauhaus abstractartmovement artmovement

text: Just a deep breath one sun salutation a minute of mediation a smile an internal thank you a walk around the block Depression can set in little by little For me it is alleviated in the same way the little by littles strung together moment by moment It s a sneaky beast setting up camp one twig at a time until it has taken up residence I have learned to keep a watchful heart eye When I have days that are dim strung together and murphy s law seems the rule of those days I know that it is time to begin again once again employing the small things stacked up on each other to climb up to the proverbial open window I have found it is important to have a list of those small things somewhere handy that I can refer to be reminded about and start laying out the path the brighter less rocky one Being happy isn t about having everything in your life be perfect Maybe it s about stringing together all the little things Ann Brashares The Peace Pause is one of those small things My daily pm pause is joined by hourly stop breathe loosen open look for what is good and right in this moment Strung together these have a miraculous effect The Peace Pause is certainly a small everyday thing that can lift us out of despair and bring us and the world some peace am pst pm and any other time you need to thegoldfinch pulitzer rembrandt stephenking nytbestseller nationalbookcriticsawardwinner warnerbrothersstudiotour amazonstudios moma peacepauseproject sistersonamission peaceinpeaceout sistersofthetravelingpants barnardcollege sidwellfriends depression smalleverydaythings opendoors openwindows donnatartt booksmadeintomovies johncrowley

name: 2019-10-03 00.06.08 2145879296975559439_moma.jpg
text: Don t forget to fall in love with yourself first Carrie Bradshaw If you feel guilty about taking time to yourself know this mama it isn t a luxury it s an essential part of being a good mom Easier said than done I know this first hand As a stay at home mom of kids with absolutely no help or family friends close by I understand how hard it is to take time for myself I often felt isolatedIn and out of touch with the rest of the world I also found myself resenting my kids not because I don t love them or regret my decision to stay home but I was just missing exploring my passions hobbies I needed my identity back I had to sit down and remember all the things I used to love to do before I had kids Once kids come into your life it s easy to bury your desires under theirs and fall prey to the dreaded mom guilt over taking some me time for yourself But our passions are what make us come alive both as people and as parents so it s critical that we continue to pursue them Personally speaking the world of beauty and fashion has always excited me excite me And here s the thing Don t think of it as indulging a passion because that s a term that s loaded with selfish connotations and who needs that Instead think of it as lighting a spark inside yourself the glow from which will also fall on your family Ignoring your passion can make you feel dull even depressed When you go to bed at night feeling like you haven t accomplished anything although you did a million chores school drop off pick up the dreaded homework time cook dinner the list goes on and on but it may well be because you didn t spend any time honoring what excites you So please take some time everyday to ether explore or enjoy what you love Get in touch with the Inner you
