text: Ren Magritte L empire des lumi res Oil on Canvas Private CollectionSold Via Christie sUSD Ren Fran ois Ghislain Magritte was born in Lessines Belgium at the end of the eldest of three sons in a manufacturing family His relatively uneventful early childhood took a turn for the tragic when his mother who had long struggled with her mental health committed suicide by drowning herself in a nearby river At the story goes the then year old Magritte was present when she was pulled from the water at which point her dress floated up to cover her face This poignant symbolism was to recur in the artist s work many times in the years that followed

text: Want your kids to eat healthy I know getting kids to eat their veggies can be stressful and a pain in the a So here are some of my favourites tips to get your kids to eat healthier without adding more stress into your life Get them to help you cook getting them involved makes them excited to try the food they ve made My GO TO is Picnic Plates This sounds fun and it gives the kids options I like to serve the food they would be less likely to eat veggies first then add some protein to their plate then something fun like cut up fruit Make fun foods like energy balls chocolate balls filled with healthy fats and nutrients but in the fun look of a Tim bit without all the processed sugar Hide vegetables in things like green pancakes and after they eat them educate them on how you made them these are made with spinach This helps them associate these foods with tasting delicious Cut food into fun shapes this makes it more visually appealing to kids and more likely to try Teach them that treats are just that treats Treats aren t bad but they are low in nutrients and won t help them feel their strongest iamryanwilliams mom momprobs kidseat kiddos mommy mommyhood momlife health nutritionist momlife kidsfood kidsplates educate teach treats protein healthyfats eat instamom boymom girlmom fitmom beat momguilt momtricks momstrong halifaxmoms moma feed dinner dinnertime

name: 2019-10-03 05.03.16 2146028852233456870_moma.jpg
text: I wanted to introduce myself share a story for all my new supports as well as old friends Right place right time is something I ve only recently found painfully untrue in moments of my life In the last few months I got an offer from what I thought was my dream job just after I signed a month lease in another town I had to reject the job and find purpose and joy in the place and time I was currently in based on these circumstances We ve all had moments like these of questioning am I where I am meant to be In these moments of doubt I think of my story about art of course I love to share I traveled the east coast two winters ago with some girlfriends hitting many art museums We walked in to the themuseumofmodernart and saw Van Gogh s Starry Night among other great pieces The one piece I was still itching to see was Salvador Dal s The Persistence of Memory Upon finding its location in the museum it said it was on leave and being shown elsewhere A few months later I applied to study abroad in Prague turning in my papers on the last day possible When I went that summer I experienced wonderful times and lots and lots of art I usually spent afternoons after class alone wandering the city and looking at art and architecture and one day I went to a Salvador Dal and Andy Warhol exhibition I was of maybe people in the museum total and I walked into a room and saw by fate The Persistence of Memory In that moment I felt this is the right place right time and that this painting had somehow been waiting for me all the way in Prague My long ramble is over but my message is that life is full of both the right times and the wrong times and at the end of the day I decide which moments I share with others value and reflect on myself I hope each of you can have a special story about art or something you love like this one day My photos go NYC Prague prague nyc salvadordali wyomingartists moma

text: Alfred Sisley The Terrace at Saint Germain Spring Oil on Canvas On ViewThe Walters Art Museum thewaltersartmuseum In this panoramic view of the Seine River valley near the town of St Germain en Laye Sisley captures the atmosphere and light conditions associated with early spring On the heights in the distance he includes the old ch teau that housed the French royal court until but he also inserts some notes of modernity including the steam tugs hauling barges on the river and the railroad bridge Sisley was born in France of English parents While enrolled in Charles Gleyre s studio in Paris he and his fellow students Claude Monet Auguste Renoir and Fr d ric Bazille began to paint outdoors in the Fontainebleau forest In he showed five paintings in the first Impressionist exhibition Of all the Impressionists he and Monet would remain the most consistent landscape painters Via thewaltersartmuseum

text: Henri Matisse The Red Studio New York If you have ever seen the painting in real life you probably would be shocked by how enormous and captivating it is The entire canvas sized x cm is flooded strikingly with vivid red The represented studio is Matisse s own displaying the artist s recent paintings sculptures and ceramics yet without the presence of the artist There is no hands on the grandfather clock as if the sense of time does not exist There is no exit in the room No one especially the centrally positioned viewer could escape from it They are trapped for eternity With such a brutal approach to colour no wonder Matisse is credited the father of Fauvism The painting was executed initially under the commission of Matisse s long time patron Sergei Shchukin Upon its completion its visual language was so foreign that Shchukin eventually rejected it I remembered when I first saw it in moma I can totally feel the aggressiveness yet I cannot help myself but be addicted to it matisse henrimatisse red art redpainting theredstudio artstudio fauvism

text: On Wednesday mornings I get to teach a preschool art class at heartwood montessori nc Today we spoke about Vincent Van Gogh We looked at some of his paintings discussed what his life was like and how misunderstood he was We are also learning a lot about kindness mindfulness and being peaceful Van Gogh is among the most famous and influential figures in the history of Western European art In just over a decade he created about artworks including around oil paintings most of which date from the last two years of his life He died at the age of just after years of mental illness and poverty vincentvangogh oilpaintings starrynight postimpressionism arthistory artlover heartwoodmontessori montessori artlesson lookatart museumofmodernart moma art

text: Ilya Bolotowsky White Circle Wow this is the second time I happened upon one of his paintings but only this one online found at moma Born in in St Petersburg Russia died in NYC Guggenheim Fellow In Bolotowsky moved from Constantinople to NYC where he studied painting at the National Academy of Design Similar in ways to Burgoyne Diller and a number of contemporaries he witnessed saw Mondrian s works and began to work in an abstract mode However the influence engage there while these works are indeed very different One major difference is this tondo or rather round format tondo is actually a word that derives from the Italian rotondo a Renaissance term which means round and in this case a circular work of art Tondi circular paintings do go way back to Greek antiquity but the form became revived again in the th century In this work the white patchwork seemed so very compelling to me almost with a feeling that it was composed of miscellaneous or incongruous parts This patchwork of fields seems to imply a covering or montage with some kind of architectural underlayment Am I right ilyabolotowsky mondrian destijl abstractpainting nonobjectiveart paintingoftheday

text: Greatest Masterpiece at friezemasters this week by Renaissance artist botticelli and his last work in private hands The work which is claimed by Spain as the country s cultural heritage required a temporary export licence from the Spanish Ministry of Culture If it sells the masterpiece will still need to come back to Spain and the Spanish authorities will have a two months window to make a counter offer Measuring inches high the portrait had originally been painted in egg tempera on panel but was transferred to canvas by a Russian restorer in Extensive areas of old restoration are visible in the sitter s dark brown hair and black tunic when viewed under ultraviolet light friezeweek masterpieces spanishministry renaissanceart artcollector museumcollection prado trinityfineart pradomuseum elpais theartnewspaper artnet moma carloorsi

text: The Cornish Coast Painted by Dame Laura Knight Born August Long Eaton Derbyshire England Died July London England aged Oil on canvas x cm Location National Museum of Wales One of the leading female artists of the twentieth century The youngest of the three daughters of Charles and Charlotte Johnson Her father abandoned the family not long after her birth and Knight grew up amid financial problems Charlotte Johnson taught part time at the Nottingham School of Art and managed to have Knight enrolled as an artisan student there paying no fees aged just At the age of fifteen and still a student herself Knight took over her mother s teaching duties when Charlotte was diagnosed with cancer and became seriously ill Laura met one of the most promising students Harold Knight then aged and determined that the best method of learning was to copy Harold s technique They became friends and married in changing her surname from Johnson At first they lived in an artist s colony in Staithes North Yorkshire until moving to Newlyn Cornwall in where they became leading members of the Newlyn School of Artists In she moved to St John s Wood which was to be the base for the remainder of her life Laura was known for painting amidst the world of the theatre and ballet in London and for being a war artist during the Second World War She was also greatly interested in and inspired by marginalised communities and individuals including Gypsies and circus performers In Harold Knight died at Colwall the couple had been married fifty eight years Laura died in aged three days before a large exhibition of her work opened at the Nottingham Castle Art Gallery and Museum museum moma metmuseum museedulouvre britishmuseum nationalgallery museodelprado vangoghmuseum brooklynmuseum text: Day San Francisco We spent the whole morning in the Moma Museum where we saw amongst others an installation of Alexander Calder which was definitely a highlight of mine Dan Flavins light installation also very cool And don t miss the cat poking through the ceiling You can see that the camera as well as Ektar are not really suited for interior dim lights We would have loved to stay the whole day but we had already booked a trip to Alcatraz On the ferry we could watch the city become smaller and smaller A view that also the prisoners sometimes could peak I had to put it new film and I chose Fujicolor C which is very different from Ektar It has more green and red hues compared to the deep blue and violet from Ektar Love the result though travel analogphotograhy travelphotography documentaryphotography olympuspenee kodakektar kodak fujifilm fujicolorC citytrip citylife usa moma alcatraz

text: William Bradford Scotch Whaler Working Through Ice Oil on Canvas On ViewVirginia Museum of Fine Arts vmfamuseum Born and raised near New Bedford Massachusetts the home port of the American whaling industry William Bradford made his career depicting the massive ships that plied the Atlantic Ocean Each spring British and American whaling vessels set out for the Arctic seeking the highly valuable products of their prey oil and bone In the summer of Bradford traveled with two photographers to the Arctic Circle to capture images of the icy North These became source material for his impressive canvases Here men stand atop the frozen ocean breaking a path through the glassy surface The harsh environment and dangerous situation are amplified by the dramatic icebergs and ever present summer sun Via vmfamuseum

text: What are your Friday Night plans Before you go do that come and enjoy this special exhibition with some drinks and hors d oeuvres starting at pm In the introductory essay to Mr Levin s exhibition catalogue Alanna Heiss ruminates As founding director of MoMA PS a large New York City institution for exhibitions I have directed and organized hundreds and hundreds of exhibitions However I have never been asked to consider the prospect of a first show of an artist so late in his career I find the resulting exhibition satisfying and simultaneously provocative it questions the art world s preoccupation with youth and the new and reminds us that important vision can reside in the eye of the old finearts photography moma ps miami wpb

text: LOUISE BOURGEOIS Arch of Hysteria art louisebourgeois favourite momaJerry Gorovoy on the artwork by Bourgeois Louise had been in psychoanalysis from all the way up to the s At the beginning of psychoanalysis with Freud there was a lot of interest in the hysterical woman who would have these contortions where the body would arch up in the air Men did it too But Louise always thought the psychoanalysts liked to see the women I mean they couldn t figure out because there was no physical reason for this kind of bodily reaction They thought it had to be some sort of mental trauma whether it was repressed memories or connected to psycho sexual repression Louise s work is to a certain degree the same thing It s psychological and emotional things manifesting in the body that she then transforms into sculpture The hanging arch figure is actually a cast of my body Louise had me lie down on a curved mound to get this shape and then the body was in a plaster mold which she then cut up to make this curve To Louise the state of hanging was this idea of fragility because it meant that the body could turn it could pivot it could spin so it wasn t a stable kind of thing Louise wanted this figure to have a high polish so that the viewer s face is caught inside the body of this contorted figure So it brings the viewer into the picture Source moma org

text: Did you know that Frieda Kahlo s infertility was the inspiration of some of her greatest pieces Intrigued by the messages manifested in Kahlo s work and surprised by the apparent lack of interest by scientists in Kahlo s clinical condition Fernando Antelo a surgical pathologist at the Harbor UCLA Medical Center set out to reassess the condition that caused Kahlo s infertility and inspired some of her greatest pieces Antelo recently conducted a review of both Kahlo s medical history and her artwork and on April he will present findings at the American Association of Anatomists Annual Meeting indicating that Kahlo s infertility was due to a condition known today as Asherman s syndrome It is unclear how many women are affected by Asherman s syndrome as it is often misdiagnosed but it is estimated that the risk of developing the syndrome from the dilation and curettage procedure ranges between percent to percent The risk increases with repeated curettage procedures Regular checking is crucial for women Join our mailing list in link in bio for more stories and research to reshape public health art fertility plantbased vegan healthyfood womenshealth womensrights pcos endemetriosis publichealth fitfood bestoftheday moma friedakahlo mexico sanfrancisco losangeles nyc brooklyn chicago bayarea sfmoma

name: 2019-10-04 06.42.46 2146803709372258923_moma.jpg
text: Childe Hassam Rue Montmartre Oil on Canvas On ViewVirginia Museum of Fine Arts vmfamuseum A young flower seller leans against a pale stone wall Her head is tilted away from us directing our eye along a bend in the street The path winds its way from the basket of vibrant red geraniums toward a complementary pop of red lurking in a blue framed window box The deep perspective and balanced elements reflect Hassam s taste for academic rationalism Yet the artist also moves beyond these conventions Injected into the natural variations of the stone wall and cobbled street are broad washes of pink and blue Hassam s experimental brush is further apparent in the blatant slashes of orchestrated color that form the cluster of trees The effect is symptomatic of the artist s syncretic style Via vmfamuseum

text: What do most girls who always dress super cute have in common Ok ok other than wearing Olive Drew They PLAN outfits ahead of time Have you ever stepped in front of your closet or dresser and stood there overwhelmed by the options Um yeah that is totally a reality right Here is a great way to plan out some outfits and be READY for the next week DO THIS Scroll through the feeds of some IG influencers you love like veronicaslook mariahbrianne courtneytoliver etc or go pin up some goodness on Pinterest Look and save the outfits that inspire you and you feel would be a good fit Share them with a friend and get some feedback Then pick a hr time slot on a Saturday or Sunday for outfit pairing Put together outfits based on the looks you love and take a pic of each one get creative and match in some hats accessories too Keep a folder of these on your phone and now you have an instant style guide in your pocket to help you pick out your outfits No more guesswork Make sure to let us know how it goes and maybe even share a video while you re doing it we d LOVE to see olivedrewclothing olivedrew mom mom momlife moments Mommy mompreneur momblogger mommylife moms momboss momtobe mommyblogger mommyandme momentos momsofinstagram momswithcameras momo momswholift MommyToBe MomofBoys momblog momoftwo moma momstyle momof MomentsOfMine momos momtogs momanddaughter

text: Anyone in ny can t miss tarsila do amaral s exhibition at moma I want to be the painter of my country wrote tarsila do amaral in Born at the end of the th century in a family of coffee plantations owners in S o Paulo tarsila as she is Known in Brazil she studied piano sculpture and drawing before leaving for Paris in to attend the academy Julian the famous school of art that attracted many international students During the following seasons in the French Capital she studied with Andr Lhote Albert gleizes and fernand l ger fulfilling what she called military service in cubism finally coming to her signed style of sensual and vibrant landscapes and common scenes The exhibition focuses on its fundamental production of the s when she sail in the worlds of art of S o Paulo and Paris and shows her involvement with an increasingly international artistic community as well as her critical role in the rise of the Modernism in Brazil In she painted abaporu for her husband the poet Oswalde De Andrade portraying an elongated and isolated figure with a cactus in bloom This historical painting inspired the manifesto of anthropophagy and became the flag of a transformative artistic movement which imagined a specifically Brazilian culture resulting from symbolic digestion or artistic cannibalism of external influences Although it is widely celebrated in her home country this is the first exhibition in the united states dedicated exclusively to the innovative art of tarsila Presenting more than works including paintings drawings notebooks photographs and historical documents extracted from collections throughout Latin America Europe and the United States tarsila do amaral inventing modern art in Brazil is a rare opportunity to explore the work This modernist boldness newyorkseries serienewyork manhattanseries MoMA iphonesia instagrammers instagrammers iphonesia

name: 2019-10-04 13.59.05 2147023311048220192_moma.jpg
text: La Femme au Chat c Painted by Edouard Manet Born January Paris France Died April Paris France aged Oil on canvas x cm Location Tate Museum London Manet had an upper class upbringing but also led a bohemian life and was driven to scandalize the French Salon public with his disregard for academic conventions and his strikingly modern images of urban life He has long been associated with the Impressionists he was certainly an important influence on them and he learned much from them himself However in recent years critics have acknowledged that he also learned from the Realism and Naturalism of his French contemporaries and even from th century Spanish painting This twin interest in Old Masters and contemporary Realism gave him the crucial foundation for his revolutionary approach Manet s modernity lies above all in his eagerness to update older genres of painting by injecting new content or by altering the conventional elements He did so with an acute sensitivity to historical tradition and contemporary reality This was also undoubtedly the root cause of many of the scandals he provoked He is credited with popularizing the technique of alla prima painting Rather than build up colors in layers Manet would immediately lay down the hue that most closely matched the final effect he sought The approach came to be used widely by the Impressionists who found it perfectly suited to the pressures of capturing effects of light and atmosphere whilst painting outdoors His loose handling of paint and his schematic rendering of volumes led to areas of flatness in his pictures In the artist s day this flatness may have suggested popular posters or the artifice of painting as opposed to its realism Today critics see this quality as the first example of flatness in modern art Manet continued to paint portraits of women still lifes landscapes and flowers even from his sickbed Succumbing to a nervous disorder most likely from tertiary syphilis Manet died a horrible death after having been reduced to a wheelchair from gangrene and even losing his leg

name: 2019-10-04 21.41.47 2147256197288452716_moma.jpg
text: Marina Abramovi alone on a big stage faced viewers on Saturday evening in front of the msub mocab This was a historic moment for the audience as much as it was for herself At some point she started explaining her piece titled Rhythm Performing in Naples she famously allowed members of the audience to pretty much do anything they pleased to her As a result one of them almost killed her while others tore her clothes apart and spat on her It was at that very moment that she revealed something fundamental both about her leaving Belgrade just one year later in and also why she became so successful abroad She briefly commented that in Rhythm she realized she was allowing the audience to bring out the worst in themselves whereas in The Artist Is Present her MoMA performance she had gone full circle and allowed the audience to bring out the best in themselves She then moved to the next subject but she had said enough and her message was loud and clear years after Rhythm the presence of Marina Abramovi is still fuelling the same sterile principled opposition in some Belgrade circles But what she proposed that evening and what she demonstrated with her whole life is that you must never be stopped by this and that greatness sometimes starts but never ends like this marinaabramovic rhythm moma theartistispresent umetnikjeprisutan predavanje historicmoment belgrade beograd belgradeart belgradeartist muzejsavremeneumetnostibeograd

text: I just completed Rip Tide It s an abstract watercolor on Yupo People seem to like my water themed pieces so I will be creating more I love working with these particular pigments as they interact so nicely with each other This original painting is available for sale in my etsy shop by tapping on the link in my bio

name: 2019-10-04 22.08.09 2147269466287739529_moma.jpg
text: I m very tired And it s very late at nightMy thoughts keep me up It s getting harder to fight I think about my failuresAnd everything I ve done wrong How I everything upIt s all a familiar song My words are getting literal I can t disguise my guiltThe hatred for myselfIn every direction it s built Well rhyming gets so hardWhen I try to write my mindBecause I m unable to find the wordsThat could shed lightEven without a rhyme or a rhythm I find it hard to articulate these dangerous thoughts I have As many writers do we have this sense of frustration because no combination of syllables can really portray the emptiness and sadness that lives in us Styron called it melancholia but not even that will suffice

text: Installation View of my most recent project A Woman with the Technology AI generated title in the exhibition Meeting the Future at SxV Museum of Modern Art sv moma Museum s inaugural exhibition This project is in collaboration with artist and technologist Yang Wang cucumberwangyang also a newinc member SxV Museum of Modern Art SV MoMA will launch the World class Exhibition This is the first exhibition in east coast of China that shows crossover works by the world famous art masters such as Picasso Dali and Andy Warhol to design masters such as Gijs Bakker Ted Noten Ruudt Peters to hundreds of representative works by more than contemporary artists and designers from countries including the UK USA the Netherlands Switzerland Germany China and Australia It creates a creative and enlightening dialogue in the fields of contemporary art fashion craft and design I ve been working on this project during my time at macdowellcolony alfred iea and newinc Thank you so much for your collaboration and support cucumberwangyang The project won t be realized without you So excited to show this project for the first time and will construct a more complex version in the upcoming exhibition in Shenzhen in November

text: Richard Estes Paris Street Scene Oil on Canvas On ViewVirginia Museum of Fine Arts vmfamuseum In the late s Estes became known for his dazzling recreations of mundane urban subjects empty city streets storefront windows and reflections on cars and the seemingly photographic precision with which he renderedthem About the time he painted Paris Street Scene Estes had begun to use multiple photographs as sources for the same image incorporating data from several perspectives In this rare non New York City scene the reflections in the plate glass window alternating with more solid architectural details enliven a Paris street Estes has signed the work in the license plate of the car closest to the center I always like to think that the paintings look very realistic but the subjects don t actually exist in this way It s a selection taking a few elements of reality of the visual elements never mind the noise the smell the actual dimensions Richard Estes Via vmfamuseum

text: Auguste Renoir Flowers Oil on Canvas On ViewThe Barnes Foundation barnesfoundation After the war ended in Renoir eventually made his way back to Paris He and some of his friends including Pissarro Monet C zanne and Edgar Degas decided to show their works on their own in Paris in which became known as the first Impressionist exhibition The group s name is derived from a critical review of their show in which the works were called impressions rather than finished paintings done using traditional methods Renoir like other Impressionists embraced a brighter palette for his paintings which gave them a warmer and sunnier feel He also used different types of brushstrokes to capture his artistic vision on the canvas Via biography com

text: For my birthday I was gifted a full day of art San Francisco never disappoints me The high I feel on life when in this city is a more beautiful feeling than any drug could ever give The art the artists the forgotten and the eccentric all of which I fancy Every time I adventure into the city I leave with many beautiful stories and many wonderful encounters with the people on the streets My friends and I were serenaded in the streets by a homeless man and his wonderful songs one of which being Happy Birthday duh The art consumes me so deeply I get lost in the colors of the city the colors of the people the colors of the streets I can t wait to say when I go home instead of when I leave My heart is full art artist sanfransisco SFart thestreetsofSF sfMoMA MoMA artist HJartworks citylife artistlife lifeofanartist cityliving HJartworks

text: Pop art is an art movement that emerged in the United Kingdom and the United States during the mid to late s The movement presented a challenge to traditions of fine art by including imagery from popular and mass culture such as advertising comic books and mundane cultural objects One of its aims is to use images of popular as opposed to elitist culture in art emphasizing the banal or kitschy elements of any culture most often through the use of irony It is also associated with the artists use of mechanical means of reproduction or rendering techniques In pop art material is sometimes visually removed from its known context isolated or combined with unrelated material Featured Roy Lichtenstein

text: Julian Opie s Back pack and Plastic Bag are two Laser cut acrylic two part statuette in a series of standing figures drawn in Australia in measuring x x cm part of an open edition They offer an insight into the minimalistic still close to heart figurative work of Opie along with an engagement with art history use of new technology obsession with the human body and work with one idea across different media from a pillar member of the newbritishsculpture movement popart julianopie julianopieart villabarolo More than two dozen of Opie s portraits landscapes and other works are in the collection of the tate Six of Opie s portraits are in the collection of the National Portrait Gallery London four portraits of the band members of Blur executed in colour print on paper one of inventor and engineer Sir James Dyson rendered by inkjet on canvas and a self portrait Julian with t shirt executed on an LCD screen with computer software nationalportraitgallery Six works are in the collection of the Museum of Modern Art New York moma

text: Edgar Degas Little Dancer Aged Fourteen Bronze tulle and silkExecuted in wax cast in bronze c Currently not on ViewPhiladelphia Museum of Art philamuseum Degas depicted young ballet dancers in performances at rehearsals or at moments of exhausted rest in numerous paintings drawings pastels and monotypes In he added sculpture to his investigation of the theme A young dancer named Marie van Goethem posed for what would be the only sculpture that Degas exhibited in his lifetime Originally executed in wax and shown in the work daringly incorporated real elements such as the dancer s tulle tutu and silk hair ribbon The sculpture was cast in bronze around several years after Degas s death Via philamuseum

name: 2019-10-06 03.54.32 2148168581232393663_moma.jpg
text: The Guitarist c Painted by Jean Baptiste Greuze Born August Tournus France Died March Louvre Paris France aged Oil on canvas x cm His early life is obscure but he studied painting in Lyons and appeared in Paris about He entered the Royal Academy as a student and worked with Charles Joseph Natoire a prominent decorative painter During the s Greuze achieved a significant reputation with his sentimental paintings of peasants or lower class people seen in humble surroundings and in the midst of theatrically emotional family situations In Greuze was admitted to the academy as a genre painter Ambitious to become a member of the academy as a history painter which was a higher rank he was so angered by his admission as only a genre painter that he refused to show his paintings at the academy s exhibitions the Salons But by that time he was already famous and could afford to ignore the Salons French painting during the th century was dominated by the rococo style Rococo painting was aristocratic in nature elegant and sensuous stylistically it depended upon soft colors complex surfaces refined textures free brushwork and asymmetrical compositions based upon the interplay of curved lines and masses Produced for highly sophisticated patrons rococo painting concentrated on aristocratic diversions decorative portraits mythological and allegorical themes frequently treated in a playful or erotic manner and idyllic pastoral scenes Greuze s pretentiously moralizing rustic dramas constituted a reaction against rococo frivolity in art by appealing to emotion they were also a revolt against the emphasis placed upon reason and science by the philosophers of the Enlightenment the intellectual movement that pervaded the first half of the th century The rising importance of the middle class and of middle class morality also played a part in the success of Greuze s cottage genre Greuze survived the French Revolution but his fame did not He died in Paris on March in poverty and obscurity

text: When one s morning begins at Christie s Post War and Contemporary Art auction preview one is bound to be struck by some fascinating art revelations This time around my discovery was related one of Germany s most praised artists of the th century Gerhard Richter With the three works by the master on display in the main room one had a chance to compare and contrast different styles of Richter s practice What I found extraordinary was the artist s ability to create polar opposite paintings in terms of style in a time span of only one year His Abstraktes Bild is a large scale non figurative abstraction work while just a year later he created Wiese Meadow a classic German landscape painting The striking contrast makes the viewer assume that the works must be decades apart and attributed to totally different periods in the artist s practice but this is not the case for the German master for whom art critics including Adrian Searle consider to be the most complicated of painters artist art gallery handmade canvas oil painting museum collector collection frieze moma artsy artmagazine gerhardrichter contemporary auction christies

text: INAUGURACI N DE MUSEO SOBRE CASTILLO EN PONFERRADATodo a punto INAUGURACI N Capic a del a o PONS FERR ART El puente en el Arte Una obra universal de la pintura cada a o en total hasta el a o del MILENARIO Santalla StrartS y QuinSan han creado la Asociaci n de Museos Virtuales cuyo fin es que todos los pueblos independientemente de su poblaci n puedan disponer de un museo de arte El lema es NING N PUEBLO SIN MUSEO Los tres primeros museos ya se han inaugurado en Lapuebla de Labarca San Juan de la Mata y Madrid El pr ximo ser el de Ponferrada OPENING OF MUSEUM ON CASTLE IN PONFERRADAEverything on point OPENING Capic a of the year PONS FERR ART The bridge in Art A universal work of painting every year in total until the year of the MILENARY Santalla StrartS and QuinSan have created the Association of Virtual Museums whose purpose is that all peoples regardless of their population can have an art museum The motto is NO PEOPLE WITHOUT MUSEUM The first three museums have already opened in Lapuebla de Labarca San Juan de la Mata and Madrid The next will be Ponferrada reinasofiamuseum museodelprado caixaforum museothyssen hermitagemuseum whitneymuseum centrepompidou nationalgallery moma museedorsay louvre met salvadordalimuseum britishmuseum tatemodern guggenheim nycart brooklynmuseum lacmamuseum gemaldegalerie artinstitutechicago ufizzi louvreabudhabi galleriaborghese gettymuseum yaleartgallery sfmoma nationalgalleryofart altepinakothek rijksmuseum

text: Indian Uttar Pradesh probably Mathura region Surya th CenturyRed sandstone On ViewVirginia Museum of Fine Arts vmfamuseum This magnificent sculpture was probably a cult image in a Hindu temple dedicated to Surya the sun god Indian sun worship was informed by Central Asian religious concepts and this influence can be seen in Surya s clothing He wears a long embroidered tunic and heavy padded boots rather than the lightweight cotton garb of the Gangetic Valley where this image was carved Though he stands straight as a pillar curved elements enliven the composition A circular halo frames his head a sweeping scarf hangs from his elbows and the female attendants flanking him stand in sinuous poses Surya s primary attribute is the lotus one of which he holds in each hand The lotus petals ornamenting his halo spread outward like the sun s rays His long scarf also terminates in lotus roundels which form halos behind the attendants Via vmfamuseum

text: Sum of Days Credit Carlito Carvalhosa An environmental and participatory sound installation a monumental voluminous construction made of soft white translucent material that hangs from ceiling to floor and takes the shape of an elliptical labyrinth This structure hides or interrupts the defined limits of its surrounding architectural space suspending visitors spatial references and allowing an experience of total immersion A system of microphones hangs from various heights and records the day s ambient noise which is played back the following day through several speakers Each day a new recording is superimposed over the previous one gradually dimming the oldest sounds into a layer of whispers Adding yet another element of sound will be periodic musical performances from within the installation The accumulation of these recordings will constitute an immaterial layering of time an auditory memory of the accidental noise inherent in everyday experience intercativeart interactiveinstallation fabric carlitocarvalhosa moma la vie art

text: Yellow Tree Red Barn c Painted by Irina Rybakova Born Vyshny Volochok Russia Oil on canvas x in Location Grenning Gallery Irina Rybakova is a famous Russian master of landscape The image of the Russian village and the village worker are her dearest subjects Her art is appreciated in museums and collections both in Russia and abroad Irina worked as part of the artistic group Academica dacha in Vyshny Volochek the oldest and well known creative base of the Union of Artists of the Russian Federation In she entered Kostroma a historic city department of Artists Union in Russia Promotes the contemporary realistic school in art in mass media Image of the Russian village and the village worker are her most dear subjects and does not like landscapes without humans museum moma metmuseum museedulouvre britishmuseum nationalgallery museodelprado vangoghmuseum brooklynmuseum artforum artbasel tatemodern instamuseum rijksmuseum whitneymuseum nationalgalleryofvictoria nationalmuseum gettymuseum curator graffiti streetart oilpainting tree irinarybakova vyshnyvolochok russia artinfluencer grenninggallery kostroma yourarttimes

text: The word science was nataliebyrne day for earthtober I drew the invention of oceancleanupofficial trillion pieces of plastic float in the great Pacific garbage patch The system consists of a metre long floater and a metre deep skirt attached below While the skirt prevents smaller plastic particles from escaping underneath The impenetrable skirt provides a downwards flow meaning marine life can pass through The floater provides buoyancy to the system and prevents plastic from flowing over it The floater concentrates the waste into one space reading for collection where it is sorted for recycling Find out more https m youtube com watch v O EAeNdTFHU climatechange marinelife planetearth oceancleanup illo illustration drawing sketch editorialillustration graphics drawing moma tate

text: Mark Rothko Untitled Maroon Over Red Acrylic on paper mounted on linen Pennsylvania Academy of Fine Arts pafacademy One of the most significant artistic pioneers of the postwar period the Russian born Rothko is principally associated with Abstract Expressionism but is also considered a forerunner of the Color Field movement which emerged from the former Rothko sought to deny the illusion of three dimensional space instead making the flatness and physical presence of the canvas an integral component of his work At the same time his paintings have been interpreted as profound meditations on the emotive or even transcendent qualities of color In this light Rothko s work has been called the most intensely personal of the New York School artists Via pafacademy

text: Claude Monet Palazzo da Mula Venice Oil on Canvas On ViewNational Gallery of Art ngadc In his late s Monet was frustrated with the Acad mie France s art establishment He hated creating formulaic artwork copying the art that hung in the Louvre and painting scenes from ancient Greek and Roman myths Although he tried to get his paintings into the Acad mie s art exhibits his art was almost always rejected Depressed and struggling to support himself and his family financially Monet jumped off a bridge in He survived his fall into the Seine and began spending time with other artists who also felt frustrated by the Acad mie s restrictions

opening was as well super good however this great exhibition celebrating of already years of pierresoulages should deserve the same attention if not more Visiting the show you realize how s quite impressive the perseverance and resistance of this pivotal frenchartist from the beginning of contemporary art in the postwar up to these days Funny thing soulages actually needed to come to US and be appreciated there at his early beginnings before his art was acknowledged as great in Europe also thanks to the inspiration and closeness with the newyorkschool The show pays homage to of his abstractions with a selection of master works spanning his career from the s up to most recent ones produced in these very last years despite the artist s age Set up with the unique elegance and scholar rigor of all L vy show this exhibition offer perfect journey into Soulages s investigation of abstraction as a poetic experience he once wrote that signifies the world by transfiguring it For me it s important to experience aesthetic shock which sets in motion our imagination our emotions our feelings and our thoughts That s the purpose of a painting and of art in general You MUST visit it and take this journey to really understand Soulages practice and evolution Sorry for not being so active in these days as I m used took time to be more active in real life taking care of other things and people I love as art And I knew you were too busy to follow what s up in friezeartfair to care about nyc but I m back so stay tuned as Oct In nyc with new moma opening and many other events will be super interesting and exciting month as well contemporaryart artecontemporanea abstractart frenchart arte artgram art artgallery artadvisor artadvisory levygorvygallery masterpieces nycartgallery text: Camille Pissarro L le Lacroix Rouen The Effect of Fog Oil on Canvas On ViewPhiladelphia Museum of Art philamuseum The eighth and final Impressionist exhibition was held in by which time the twelve year old movement was no longer regarded as radical As the oldest of the artists who exhibited with the Impressionists Camille Pissarro may have felt a particular need to stay abreast of current developments and keep his work fresh The bold optical experiments of the young Georges Seurat who used small dabs of juxtaposed color to build pictures of great effect and intensity intrigued Pissarro who embraced Neo Impressionism and specifically the pointillist style for four years in the late s Pissarro created the present painting from an earlier composition in his studio rather than in front of the motif which was his usual practice He had visited Rouen in and made several drawings and etchings of the Seine that he consulted five years later when painting this foggy view of factories and barges on the river An industrial landscape dominated by a smoke belching chimney the scene is rendered with great beauty in a subtle range of colors The broad flat frame with its laurel leaf border was designed by Pissarro for this picture though it may originally have been painted white Via philamuseum

text: Today is Ken s birthday and what a life and journey it has been Traveling the world with Dr Margaret Mead as a young man Ken documented indigenous communities across the globe in a collaboration which lasted over years and resulted in two books which they co authored more books would follow as would an invitation from Edward Steichen to be represented in the collections of the Museum of Modern Art one of or so museums worldwide in whose collections Ken s work sits His images often illuminate our interconnectedness and the complexities of human relationships as Mead noted and whether they be of celebrities or everyday life have captivated audiences during a career which has spanned nearly years Happy Birthday Ken kenheyman happybirthday MoMA museumofmodernart margaretmead interconnectedness humanity leonardbernstein andywarhol jamesrosenquist popart popartists

text: Footprint IX InkOnPaper X cm alma contemporary art gallery This figure is travelling to Milan I am very glad that the figures from the composition of the ten forms titled FOOTPRINT which were exhibited at the st Larnaca Biennale have already been distributed in various places Four of them remained in Cyprus They spoke to the hearts of two sisters who loved them and kept them at their home in Nicosia And now this one is departing for Milan Italy at a couple s home I am wondering where the five remaining ones will go To be exact I am looking forward to it I hope the couple will enjoy the work as its symbolisms and energy will be communicating with them in a perpetual way in their personal space mmkfrankfurt moma georgiakarampelou mumok milanoart artlondon artbaselcities

name: 2019-10-07 06.53.24 2148983385132085590_moma.jpg
text: Dear Mommas It s okay to not do it like the book your best friend or even your mom it s okay to do it the way that fits you and your little one It s totally fine if you didn t make it breastfeeding or that your yo still likes the boob or you can t get him off the bottle it s okay that your yo still likes a binky to go to bed or that your yo sleeps with you every night It s okay that you ve cried yourself to sleep wondering if you did anything right the entire week It s fine that your kids socks don t match or that you forgot picture day or that you fed them all cereal for dinner It s okay that you put them to bed at so that you could just have an hour of silence You seasoned mommas it s okay that the younger moms do it differently that they have new gadgets and gizmos that you didn t have Know what else they have that you didn t have Social media and the pressure to constantly be perfect the feeling of never being a post worthy mother and the daily opportunity to compare themselves to the other moms the ones whose kids always have on matching outfits and never seem to get dirty Young moms give yourself some grace know that no one is perfect those outfits don t always match and those kids get nasty Know that we have all cried to ourselves while trying to just keep a baby alive and please please know that social media is only the highlight reel of peoples lives We don t need to post the ugly we don t want the on this day reminders Seasoned moms please with all the love in my heart stop pretending like you never experienced those hard times stop giving your option like you never thought you screwed a kid up Reach out to those young moms tell them you understand and that it s not easy but so worth the battle Hold that baby let them nap let them have a coffee by themselves or go to the grocery store Let them know that you struggled too I promise you those sweet conversations will feed their souls much more than your I did it like stories Lastly all of these thoughts were brought on by me holding my almost yo baby during church Because it works for us and I don t care what others think

text: Demos un peque o paseo en el tiempo y remont monos a principios del siglo pasado Machu Picchu acababa de ser descubierta Augusto B Legu a era el presidente y Mart n Chambi empezaba con tan solo a os a ganarse la vida en las minas de oro de Carabaya donde descubrir a su verdadera pasi n La fotograf a Mart n Chambi es considerado como un pionero en la fotograf a de retrato y valorado como un impulsador de la fotograf a de tipo tnica y testimonio biol gico La sociedad peruana de ese entonces tuvo mucha suerte ya que un gran artista de la luz como Chambi los retrat para la posteridad Parte de su obra ha sido expuesta en galerias de todo el Per as como en el extranjero El MOMA Fundaci n Telef nica en Madrid Actualmente el trabajo de Mart n Chambi est celosamente guardado por sus nietos quienes son los encargados de difundir el trabajo de este gran artista y fot grafo peruano todo un orgullo para Latinoam rica chambi referentes fotografia leyend portrait bw machupichu cuzco moma madrid retrato indigena pionero

text: An uncompassionate crowd of are tensely sitting in a stadiumbloodthirstily waiting for a cruel spectaclethey call a bulllfight which is actually a bull harass and This brutal bloodsportis celebrated as a national artformin Spainso the matadors bullfighters strut around proudlyin their suits of golden threadto loud cheers and excited applause The bull frightened suffering is harassed and killed in three stages The first stage is called tercio de varas the lancing third when armoured horse mounted lancersuse a long sharp lanceto spear the bull behind his shoulder musclesto weaken the bull s neck musclesand begin the bull s loss of blood The second stage is called tercio de banderillas the third of banderillas when the matador attacks the bleeding weakening bullwith banderillas sharp barbed sticks stabbing the banderillas above the shoulder blades of the bullto anger and agitate the frightened bull fighting for his life The third stage is called tercio de muerte the third of death when the matador baits the bullwith a red capethen stabs the bull with a steel swordaiming for his heartbut often missingleaving the bull suffering multiple stab woundsbleeding slowly miserably dying I wonder when will this barbaric bull harass and be banned in all nations

text: Arguably Frieze Art Fair is an equivalent of London Fashion Week for the art world This is the place where the trends are set for the local and global art scene Galleries have different strategies when it comes to selecting artists for their displays Some opt for debuting their rising stars other prefer to showcase the big blue chip names Somehow every year there are a few artists that simply dominate the fair For some mysterious reason a number of galleries choose to display works by a particular artist preferring him or her to all the rest This time round a world renowned Italian painter and sculpture Alberto Burri led the way I have never seen so many works by this key representative of postminimalism and Arte Povera at the same place and time I had a feeling I was attending his retrospective friezeartfair friezemasters albertoburri artepovera italian art postminimalism artist art gallery handmade canvas oil painting museum collector collection frieze moma artsy artmagazine

text: Jacob Jordaens St Paul Oil on Wood s On ViewVirginia Museum of Fine Arts vmfamuseum Starting in the early s Jordaens painted a number of saints in a half length format probably for sale singly or in pairs for use in small chapels and private devotion The practice of using paintings as devotional aids was still used in the Catholic Southern Netherlands though they had been abandoned in the Protestant North Saul of Tarsus a diligent persecutor of Christians underwent a spectacular conversion changed his name to Paul and became a Christian missionary to the Gentiles The symbols that identify him here are the sword with which he was executed and a book which stands for his learning and his authorship of the Epistles Via vmfamuseum

text: Titov tajni bunker u kojem biste mogli pre ivjet i nuklearnu katastrofu Titov Bunker aka D ARK u Konjicu godinama je bio dobro uvana tajna Gra en je u tajnosti od do kako bi se u slu aju atomske katastrofe tu sklonili Tito i njegovih najbli ih suradnika Ovaj impozatni prostor le i na m prostora metara ispod povr ine zemlje Bunker je sagra en sa namjerom da u slu aju atomskog rata funkcionira kao centar vojnih operacija i skloni te za predsjednika Tita njegovu familiju i najbli e saradnike Bunker je bio predvi en da osigura neometan ivot ljudi tijekom mjeseci Do ih godina izgradnja u koju je investirano milijardi ameri kih dolara i postojanje ovog bunkera bila je najstro e uvana vojna tajna Za vrijeme raspada Jugoslavije JNA je naredila ru enje kompleksa kako ne bi pao pod kontrolu vlasti BiH ali je vojni odred odbio izvr iti naredbu i umjesto toga predao bukner vladi Objekt je danas muzej u kojemu se odr avaju kulturne manifestacije poput Bijenala suvremen umjetnosti Tito TitovBunker Konjic d ark BiH JNA Jugoslavija MoMA MuzejSuvremeneUmjetnosti Balkan Bosnia bunker betonskispavaci

text: Exclusive Title The New Dualistic Moiety Piece Vogue Re imagined Series Inspired by the intelligently beautiful vogueitalia October Issue cover I crafted this alternate narrative in order to make real my own dreamed reality This story speaks to the duality of nature about how differences highlight their opposites and how human beauty is something that transcends the body willowsmith and c syresmith are united in couture made by guopei The garment represents the world and le grand palais the splendours of the universe In this context the Smiths represent the worldly emergence of those similar differences that we find throughout all of our natures I play with the redefinition of hyper masculinity and antique notions of male beauty exhibited through the ludovicdedsaintsernin breastplate Reworking classical ideas about colour and ornamentation the new nomadic look in dior French fuchsia tones with hints of primary colour from xanderzhou allowed me to speak stylistically about what exists at the most primitive grounds of male creative expression Willow holds many symbols also her jewellery from giambattistavalliparis and headgear from james t merry meld into a discourse about new femininity and how its bounds contain natural diversities Overall the piece is symbolist with hints of surrealism but remains grounded but in an exalted sense Much more meaning can be found herein especially in the references to basquiat and hieronymusbosch and how their presence speak about alternate states in our time Esteemed Audience riccardobe lordrochester g testino ferdinandoverderi alessiaglaviano jadapinkettsmith rocnation moma VogueItalia IbKamara digitalcollage fashioncollage Vogue art amby editorialfashion editorialstyling editorials creativedirection paris couture retouching sainthoax willowsmith artforum artandcommerce tatemodern Guggenheim maisonnargiela artcollective arte digitalart mixedmedia luxury

text: G za Perneczky s exhibition opening next week at Capa Center Budapest Mirrors G za Perneczky s conceptual photography from the sThe opening will take place on October pm with an opening speech by D vid Feh r The exhibition is the largest exhibition ever conceived for the artist It will be a milestone in the reception of G za Perneczky s oeuvre and will give a unique overview of the conceptual photographic work created in Cologne in the early s shortly after the dissident s emigration In addition to well known works some of which will be shown as original special editions lesser known works from Perneczky s archive will also be exhibited Many of the collected works will be presented to the international public in Budapest for the first time including mm experimental film as part of the scientific reappraisal of Perneczky s entire oeuvre More info HU https capacenter hu kiallitasok perneczky geza tukrok EN https capacenter hu en kiallitasok geza perneczky mirrors capacenter gezaperneczky soloexhibition conceptualphotography s hungarianneoavantgarde photoexhibition conceptualart experimentalfilm contemporaryart qcontemporary photography silverprint vintagephotos moma metropolitanmuseum centrepompidou dissident

text: Jean Michel Basquiat Self Portrait oil acrylic oilstick graphite and pen on paper collage on wood with metal attachments in parts CURRENT EXHIBITIONBasquiat s Defacement The Untold StoryUntil November On ViewGuggenheim Museum guggenheim This exhibition takes as its starting point the painting The Death of Michael Stewart informally known as Defacement created by Jean Michel Basquiat in The work commemorates the fate of the young black artist Michael Stewart at the hands of New York City Transit Police after allegedly tagging a wall in an East Village subway station Originally painted on the wall of Keith Haring s studio within a week of Stewart s death Basquiat s painting was a deeply personal lamentation that has rarely been exhibited in a public context With The Death of Michael Stewart as its centerpiece this exhibition examines Basquiat s exploration of black identity his protest against police brutality and his attempts to craft a singular aesthetic language of empowerment Several of the works on view by Basquiat illustrate his sustained engagement with the subject of state authority in the paintings depicting police figures Other works explore his canonization of historical black figures especially the jazz legend Charlie Parker who was perhaps Basquiat s favorite hero to depict on canvas An early self portrait created the same year as The Death of Michael Stewart suggests Basquiat s keen self awareness as a black artist navigating a predominantly white and often hostile art world Via guggenheim

text: MUSEO DE SAN JUAN DE LA MATAEL FUEGO EN EL PRADOHomenaje al Museo del Prado en su Bicentenario Complementa y ampl a la exposici n anterior sobre el mismo tema pero con obras pertenecientes al Museo del Prado Vel zquez Rubens Goya El Bosco Cossiers Y como plato fuerte Un cuadro viviente Santalla StrartS y QuinSan han creado la Asociaci n de Museos Virtuales cuyo fin es que todos los pueblos independientemente de su poblaci n puedan disponer de un museo de arte El lema es NING N PUEBLO SIN MUSEO MUSEUM OF SAN JUAN DE LA MATATHE FIRE IN THE PRADOTribute to the Prado Museum in its BicentennialIt complements and extends the previous exhibition on the same subject but with works belonging to the Prado Museum Vel zquez Rubens Goya El Bosco Cossiers And as a main course A living picture Santalla StrartS and QuinSan have created the Association of Virtual Museums whose purpose is that all peoples regardless of their population can have an art museum The motto is NO PEOPLE WITHOUT MUSEUM reinasofiamuseum museodelprado caixaforum museothyssen hermitagemuseum whitneymuseum centrepompidou nationalgallery moma museedorsay louvre met salvadordalimuseum britishmuseum tatemodern guggenheim nycart brooklynmuseum lacmamuseum gemaldegalerie artinstitutechicago ufizzi louvreabudhabi galleriaborghese gettymuseum yaleartgallery sfmoma nationalgalleryofart altepinakothek rijksmuseum

text: Does the position you currently hold not allow for work and life balance so you feel stuck Are you tired of being overwhelmed and exhausted with your to do list at home and at work but don t know what to do to mitigate it all In my upcoming Live Webinar entitled Work It Life It Self It I share the initial steps you must take to begin to achieve the success of balancing work and life You will learn how to Let go of the mom guilt Establish equality in your home Establish an action plan to get to the next level in your careerAs a Christian Career Strategist I prepare working Millennial moms to get promoted so they can achieve success while having a Balanced lifestyle As a result of working with me moms have less stress are on a clear path to promotion which leads to an increase in income and achieve the work and life balance they need With the right strategies goals and action steps working moms can excel at home and work Join me this Friday October th from pm to pm EST for this Live Webinar where I debunk the thought that you can t have work and life balance and show you the initial steps of how you can excel both at home and at work If you cant make the live the replay will be emailed to those who register Click on the link to register for the Complimentary Live Webinar https buff ly oaMwYn worklife WorkLifeBalance careermom careerwomen workingmoms mochamoms workingwomen balance momsdoingit momlife workingmom promotion careerstruggles careergoals momguilt momguiltisreal momtips momofmultiples moma thismama mompreneur womenownedbusiness careercoach dmvcareercoach dmvevents webinar careerwebinar training thecareerstrategist christiancareercoach

text: The works of the important ChenZhen will be part this October in the opening of the newMoMA Stunning new galleries and spaces for performance and events will transform the Museum Along with these physical changes we ll be showing our collection in new and unprecedented ways to bring more voices and perspectives to our galleries Every visit will be an opportunity to discover something new and to connect to art and ideas that spark curiosity debate and inspiration Together we ll explore the ideas that shape our world and find inspiration in the art of our time Glenn D Lowry The David Rockefeller Director Repost themuseumofmodernart The final work ChenZhen made before his death in Un Village sans frontie res is an assembly of unique miniature houses made of candles and positioned on children s chairs sourced from around the world The artist drew from his experiences in Brazil mentoring impoverished children who used candles to build models of their dream houses here the inclusion of chairs and the works small size expand upon his keen interest in domestic spaces as a primary site of intimacy security and vulnerability See it on view in the newMoMA Image Chen Zhen Un Village sans fronti re Wood chair and candles Enid A Haupt Fund Photo by Duccio Benvenuti GalleriaContinua ChenZhen MOMA NewYork themuseumofmodernart

text: Florence Knoll Three Seater Leather Benches By Knoll Stamped Signed Fabulous pair of Florence Knoll Three Seater benches by Knoll studio finished in colour Parchment in Volo leather on a chrome base stamped Florence Knoll Knoll Studio Designed in as what Florence Knoll modestly referred to as one of the fill in pieces that no one else wants to do the Florence Knoll Bench now stands as a defining example of modern design Consistent with all of her designs the bench has a spare geometric profile that reflects the objective perfectionism and rational design approach Florence Knoll learned from her mentor Mies van der Rohe Dimensions Height inches cmWidth inches cmDepth inches cmLove these available now knoll moma florenceknoll midcenturydesign knollstudio florenceknollbassett interiordesigners knollinc midcenturymodern interiorstylist chairs splendidantiques stdibs newyork london paris losangeles la ny hk dubai
